1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 {For more than a century, the Open Variation has been one of the most
controversial openings in the whole opening theory. Decades of popularity have
alternated with even longer periods of oblivion. The best way of proving that
truth is relative in this system is by quoting the opinions of two outstanding
grandmasters and theoreticians. Tarrasch, who has used it constantly and quite
successfully, to the point that he is not considered the godfather of the
variation, wrote that in the starting position Black has an advantage, due to
his space advantage in the centre and on the queenside, the active minor
pieces (with a special mention for the knight on e4) and the weakness of
White's pawn on e5. Decades later, Keres had an opposite view, based on
precisely the same elements. He considered Black's opening unsatisfactory
because of the vulnerability of the central knight, weakness of Black's
queenside and White's attacking chances due to his strong pawn on e5! Far be
it from me to argue with the opinions above. On the contrary, I would
confidently say that both Tarrasch and Keres were right! The final outcome of
the opening depends precisely on the fate of these three elements, the central
knight, the queenside structure and the pawn on e5. In this article, I will
exemplify both points of view, in order to offer as complete a picture as
possible. I will start with a model game for Keres' philosophy.} 9. Nbd2 {
This was the first time Karpov played this move in Merano.} Nc5 10. c3 d4 11.
Bxe6 Nxe6 {Anticipating the main theme in later examples, a blocking knight on
e6 can easily be Black's best piece. It not only prevents a break with e5-e6
but also controls several important central squares.} 12. cxd4 Ncxd4 {For a
long time this line was considered comfortable for Black. But Karpov's novelty
(apparently analyzed by Polugaevsky and Geller in Moscow while Karpov was
taking a break from the Ruy Lopez with two Italian games), brought new life
into the variation and launched a whole new fashion trend.} 13. Ne4 {The
knight immediately makes use of the square which became available after the
thematic central break.} Be7 14. Be3 {This is an illustrative moment for
Keres' idea about Black's pieces' instability. Due to White's space advantage,
Black cannot maintain his outpost.} Nxf3+ $6 {Caught by surprize, Kortschnoj
makes a huge concession, helping White to develop actively.} ({True,} 14... c5
{would leave him hanging after} 15. b4 $1) ({But later it was established that
} 14... Nf5 15. Qc2 O-O 16. Rad1 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Qc8 {is entirely playable for
Black.}) 15. Qxf3 $16 O-O 16. Rfd1 {As revealed below, this square belongs
precisely to this rook. But even without concrete variations, we can rely on
what Lasker used to call "common sense in chess". White has two open files, he
should be prepared to control them with the rooks.} Qe8 $2 {Probably the most
unfortunate queen retreat.} ({True,} 16... Qc8 {prevents the game combination:}
17. Nf6+ $6 gxf6 18. exf6 Bd6 {With the queen on e8} 19. Rd4 {would win but now
} Nxd4 $19 {defends g4. But White has the simple 17.Rac1, threatening Rd6.
This not only justifies 16.Rfd1 but also offers a hint about the relative
weakness of the queenside, mentioned by Keres.}) ({With respect to the game
move} 16... Qb8 {has the merit of leaving the f8-rook free, allowing Black to
meet} 17. Nf6+ Bxf6 18. exf6 {with} g6 {, more or less consolidating the
kingside. True, White would retain a huge space advantage with} 19. Rd7 $16)
17. Nf6+ $1 {"The strong pawn on e5 offers White attacking chances".} Bxf6 (
17... gxf6 $2 18. exf6 Bd6 {runs into} 19. Rd4 $1 Kh8 20. Rh4 $18) 18. exf6 {
This can already be considered a moral defeat for the knight on e6, which has
lost its blocking function.} Qc8 ({Black has no time to consolidate as} 18...
g6 {loses the exchange to} 19. Bh6) 19. fxg7 Rd8 ({Black decides that this
pawn is his king's best defender.} 19... Kxg7 {loses on the spot to} 20. Bh6+
$1 Kxh6 21. Qf6+ Kh5 22. Rd5+) (19... Nxg7 20. Rd4 {also offers White a slow
but decisive attack.}) 20. h4 $1 {As simple as that. The pawn is rushing to h6,
to sustain its colleague.} c5 21. Rac1 Qc7 22. h5 Qe5 23. h6 Qxb2 24. Rd7 Rxd7
25. Qxa8+ Rd8 26. Qxa6 {The game is over. White has an extra pawn and any
ending will be hopeless for Black, whose king is stuck on g8 or f7.} Qe2 $1 27.
Rf1 Rd1 28. Qa8+ Rd8 29. Qc6 b4 30. Qa4 $1 Qd3 31. Rc1 Qd5 32. Qb3 Qe4 33. Qc2
Qxc2 $2 34. Rxc2 $18 f5 35. f4 $1 Kf7 36. g4 Rd5 37. gxf5 Rxf5 38. Rd2 Rf6 39.
Rd7+ Kg8 40. f5 $1 Rxf5 41. Re7 Nxg7 42. Rxg7+ Kh8 43. Rc7 Kg8 44. Bxc5 Rg5+
45. Kf2 Rg6 46. Be3 {In this game, Keres' evaluation prevailed over Tarrasch'
only because of the unfortunate exchange on f3. Here is a later game by
Kortschnoj in which Tarrasch's philosophy will prevail.} 1-0

