1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Ng5 10. c3 d4 11. Bxe6 Nxe6 12. cxd4 Ncxd4 13. Ne4 Be7 {The first
13 moves were the same as in the previous game.} 14. a4 {Introducing another
important element from White's arsenal. Attacking b5 can be effective in many
positions (an example being 13.a4 in Line 14 from the theory database), but
with development incomplete it looks rather premature. White probably wanted
to combine the ideas behind Karpov's 13.Ne4 and 13.a4 (played in the last game
of the same match), but the resulting cocktail is not too tasty.} O-O 15. Be3
Nf5 $1 {Not repeating the mistake from the previous game.} 16. Qe2 {White
tries to provoke either ...b5-b4 or ...c7-c6, weakening c4 or d6, respectively.
} Qb8 17. Bg5 $6 {White probably wanted to weaken Black's control over c5, in
order to make his queenside attack more effective. But moving with the bishop
for the second time along the same diagonal is a waste of time.} ({It would
have made more sense to exchange Black's strong knight on e6 with} 17. Nfg5 {
even though after} Bxg5 18. Nxg5 Nxe3 $11 {the position is just equal.}) 17...
h6 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Nc3 {This apparently consistent move, attacking b5, is,
in fact, a mistake.} ({It was not too late to stay close to equality with} 19.
Rfc1 {, completing development. We can conclude that White's inaccuracies were
of the same kind as Kortschnoj capture on f3 in the previous game.}) 19... b4
$3 {Played without any pre-concepts, this marks the turning point in the game.
Black allows White to reach his goal, the control over the c4-square, but the
time wasted in the process will prevent him from enjoying this symbolic
success. It will soon turn out that the only one having real queenside
weaknesses will be White.} 20. Ne4 Rd8 21. Qc4 ({The queen is not the best
blocking piece, but transferring the knight to c4 would be too time-consuming,
allowing Black to reach an overwhelming activity:} 21. Ned2 Qb7 22. Nc4 Nf4 23.
Qe3 Rd4 $3 {Did anybody say that Black's pieces are vulnerable in the centre?
Just try to capture the undefended rook and we will see.} 24. Na5 ({Forced as
if} 24. Rac1 Nf5 {White will get under a knight fork.}) ({while after} 24. b3
Nf5 25. Qe1 {Black gets a decisive attack with} Nxg2) 24... Qd5 25. Qb3 Rd8 26.
Qxd5 R4xd5 27. Nc4 Nd3 $17 {With clear domination.}) 21... Qb6 22. Rfd1 Qa5 {
Starting at this moment, the pawn on e5 corresponds with Tarrasch' description
as "weak".} 23. b3 ({White is not prepared for the generally desirable
exchange of the knight on e6:} 23. Nd4 Nxd4 24. Rxd4 Qxe5 25. Rxd8+ Rxd8 26.
Qxb4 a5 27. f4 ({Or} 27. Qe1 Qxb2 $17 {with a sound extra pawn.}) 27... Qe6 $17
{The White king will soon become vulnerable.}) 23... Ng6 24. Ng3 Qc5 $1 {
Black focuses on White's queenside weaknesses, as the e5-pawn is not that
important at this stage.} ({But} 24... Nxe5 {was strong, too:} 25. Nxe5 Qxe5
26. Qxb4 c5 27. Qc4 Rd4 28. Rxd4 cxd4 $17 {The passed pawn sustained by all of
Black's pieces is very threatening.}) 25. Qe4 Qc3 26. Rdc1 ({White could have
kept the pawn on b3 only by giving up the central one under very unpleasant
circumstances:} 26. Rdb1 Nc5 27. Qe1 Qxe1+ 28. Nxe1 Nxe5 $19 {Black has an
extra pawn and a dominating position.}) 26... Qxb3 27. Rcb1 Qc3 28. Rc1 Qd3 29.
Qxb4 Ngf4 {White has retrieved the pawn, but Black is very active and has a
passed c-pawn. At this stage, it is clear that the queenside structure favours
Black.} 30. Ra3 ({Or} 30. Qc4 Rab8 $17 {, keeping control over the two open
files.}) 30... a5 ({It will soon turn out that} 30... c5 $1 {would have been
more useful.} 31. Rxc5 $2 {does not work due to the back rank weakness. The
most convincing answer is} Qxa3 $1) 31. Qb3 {With the pawn on c5, Black could
now have played 31...c4 and if 32.Rxc4? Qd1+ followed by ...Ne2+ soon.} Rab8
32. Qxd3 Nxd3 33. Rd1 {Black's position remains very promising, but knowing
Kortschnoj and judging from the ulterior course of the game, the players were
in time trouble already.} Nef4 ({There was no need to remove the knight from
e6.} 33... Ndc5 $17 {would have doomed the pawn on a4.}) 34. h4 Kf8 35. Ne4 Nb4
$15 36. Rxd8+ $6 Rxd8 37. Rc3 $2 Ne2+ 0-1

