1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 {After taking a first look at the duality of the general evaluation and
the tight connection between the three essential elements mentioned by both
Tarrasch and Keres, we will now deal with White's attempts to attack the weak/
strong queenside structure. There are two basic methods of achieving that:
a2-a4 and piece pressure on d5. We will find out that they can be logically
connected to each other, too.} 9. Be3 Be7 10. c3 Nc5 11. Bc2 Bg4 12. Nbd2 Ne6
13. Qb1 Bh5 14. a4 {White threatens to freeze Black's queenside with b2-b4,
followed by pressure on b5.} ({Starting with} 14. b4 {runs into} a5 {, and
Black's pressure on the a-file offers him counterchances.}) 14... b4 $1 {
The consequences of the pawn moves' sequence are multiple. Black can molest
the enemy queen with ...bxc3 and ...Rb8 while after the desirable Nb3,
increasing control over c5 and d4, the knight will have lost the natural
defence by the a2-pawn. But at the same time, Black has partly lost his
stability in the centre in view of the threat c3-c4.} 15. a5 $1 {The last two
moves are typical for such situations. Black has prevented b2-b4 and White has
done the same with the consolidating ...a6-a5. In some cases (not very
probable in this position, though), the last move can also be a way to prepare
Ba4, more or less forcing the knight to retreat further from the central
squares.} Bg6 ({Strategically a sound decision, forcing the exchange of the
light-squared bishops. But another way of preparing castling was} 15... bxc3
16. bxc3 Rb8 17. Qa2 O-O $11 {White does not get much out of} 18. Ba4 $6 {
due to} d4 $17) 16. Bxg6 fxg6 $2 {Chekhov must have played this on autopilot,
as this is the standard way of recapturing. But now White has the chance to
exploit Black's delayed castling.} ({Under these concrete circumstances} 16...
hxg6 {was the correct move for two different reasons. The simplest of them is
that it allows meeting} 17. c4 {with} Rh5 $15 {. We will see the second
difference in the line below.}) 17. Nb3 $2 ({Missing his chance with} 17. c4 $1
$14 {In order to avoid a blockade on c4,} d4 $2 {looks logical, but it runs
into} 18. Qe4 {. Had Black played 16...hxg6, he could now simply castle, but
here this is impossible because after 19.о Bxc6 the knight on e6 is hanging.
And if} Qd7 {,} 19. Nxd4 $1 {wins an important pawn.}) 17... bxc3 18. bxc3 Rb8
19. Qa2 Qd7 20. Rfd1 O-O {After castling, things reenter the normal course for
Black. The king's rook is on an open file and the knights are defended by the
queen.} 21. c4 $2 {"Better late than never" does not apply here.} ({Facing the
positional threat ...Rxf3, White should have thought of his safety already
with:} 21. Nbd4 Nexd4 22. cxd4 Rb5 23. Qe2 (23. Bd2 {allows} Rxf3 24. gxf3 Nxd4
$17 {with overwhelming play for the exchange.}) 23... Nxa5 24. Bd2 Nc4 25. Rxa6
$11 {White has retrieved the pawn and his compact structure compensates for
Black's superior activity.}) 21... Rxf3 $1 {Not only spoiling White's kingside
structure but also removing an important defender of the d4-square.} ({But
even in the absence of this resource, (for example had he played ...hxg6
instead of ...fxg6), Black could have maintained his stability with} 21... Nb4
$11) 22. Rxd5 (22. gxf3 d4 {yields Black absolute stability in the centre and
attacking ideas.} 23. Kg2 (23. f4 {runs into} Ng5 $1 {and if} 24. fxg5 Qg4+ 25.
Kh1 Qf3+ 26. Kg1 dxe3 $19 {The White knight is too far from the king to help
and also hanging.}) 23... Rd8 24. Qa4 Bc5 25. Ra2 Qe8 26. Bd2 g5 $17 {With a
systematic attack against White's chronic weaknesses.}) (22. cxd5 {also works
out well for Black:} Rxe3 23. fxe3 (23. dxc6 {leads to a similar ending as in
the game:} Qxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Rexb3 $17) 23... Nb4 $17 {The queen does not have
good squares.} 24. Qb1 (24. dxe6 {loses material:} Qxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Nxa2 $19) (
24. Qd2 Qxd5 25. Qxd5 Nxd5 26. Rxd5 Rxb3) 24... Nxd5 25. e4 Nc5 $17 {With a
material advantage for Black.}) 22... Rxe3 23. Rxd7 Rexb3 $17 {Black has three
well-coordinated minor pieces for the queen and firm control over the b-file.}
24. c5 $5 {The only dynamic resource, opening the a2-g8 diagonal.} Bxc5 (24...
Kf8 $1 {would have neutralized White's idea. The pawn on c5 was not going
anywhere.}) 25. Rd3 {White gets some relief now by exchanging one rook. It is
worth mentioning that now and in the whole next phase, the stability of
Black's minor pieces will determine the evaluation of the position. Even
though the game has partly lost its typical Open Spanish contours, the
argument between Tarrasch and Keres on this issue remains valid until deep
into the endgame.} Ncd4 26. Rxb3 Rxb3 27. Rb1 Ra3 28. Qd5 Kf7 29. Qd7+ Be7 {
As long as Black's minor pieces are defended, only he can think of playing for
a win.} 30. f4 $2 {White overestimates the strength of the threat Rb8.} ({
He could have reached some static equality with} 30. Rd1 c5 31. Qd5 {It is
hard for Black to make progress, as} Rxa5 $2 32. Rxd4 {loses material based on
the double pin.}) 30... Ne2+ $2 {I assume that both players were in time
trouble by now. But the ensuing mutual mistakes are instructive.} ({Black
could have bravely grabbed two pawns:} 30... Rxa5 $1 31. Rb8 Nxf4 $1 {The
knights are indirectly defending each other and the king has got the e6-square
to escape the attack.}) 31. Kh1 N2d4 32. g4 $2 (32. g3 $16 {would have renewed
the threat Rb8, as with f4 defended the black knight on e6 cannot clear the
e6-square anymore.}) 32... h5 33. gxh5 ({After} 33. Rb8 Ra1+ {, the mutual
attacks will match each other, resulting in a perpetual check:} 34. Kg2 Nxf4+
35. Kf2 $1 (35. Kg3 Rf1 {offers Black a decisive attack, as his king escapes
easily:} 36. Qe8+ Ke6 37. Qc8+ Kd5 38. Qb7+ c6 39. Qxe7 Rf3+ 40. Kh4 Rh3+ 41.
Kg5 Nde6+) 35... Ra2+ {The White king cannot escape the checks.}) 33... gxh5
34. Qd5 $2 {Retreating just when the signal to the attack resounded.} (34. Rb8
Ra1+ {would lead to similar play as in the previous line.}) 34... g6 35. Rd1 c5
{Black has consolidated and once again his position is preferable.} 36. Kg1 h4
37. Kh1 h3 38. Qa8 Ra2 {The pawn on a6 is taboo due to ...Nf3 and mate.} 39. f5
$6 {A typical time trouble swindle.} Nxf5 $2 (39... gxf5 40. Rg1 Bd8 $17 {
would have parried all threats, maintaining the coordination and two passed
pawns.}) 40. Qxa6 {Now this becomes possible.} Ned4 $2 41. Qc4+ 1-0

