{In the next game, the sequence a2-a4, ...b5-b4 will be followed by a
different scenario, even though the main issue will be the same: White's
pressure on d5. And Black's minor piece activity in the endgame will once
again be the main theme.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Bc2 O-O 11. Nbd2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7
13. Nbd4 Nd8 14. Bb3 c6 {White seems to be more harmoniously developed, but
Black's solid centre allows him to plan his regrouping to a more natural piece
configuration. His goal is to play ...Kh8, ...Bg8 ad finally .. .c6-c5. At the
same time the knight on e4 is well defended and active, while White will find
it difficult to develop his queen's bishop, as Be3 would typically run into . .
.f5-f4.} 15. a4 ({It is important to examine the consequences of} 15. Nxe6 Nxe6
16. Nd4 {Aiming to exchange the blocking knight.} a5 {For the time being,
Black does not have to release the tension and can fight for the control of
the light squares with ...a5-a4.} 17. f3 {looks like the soundest plan, but
this allows Black to bring the reserve knight closer to e6.} (17. a4 b4 $11 {
does not improve White's chances. The thematic} 18. c4 $6 {reveals the
unfavourable consequences of the operation initiated by a2-a4.} Nxd4 19. Qxd4
Nc5 {Suddenly the bishop is unstable and passive.} 20. Bc2 f4 {Restricting the
other bishop, too.} 21. cxd5 Qxd5 22. Qxd5+ cxd5 $15 {with excellent control
on the whole board.}) (17. Nxe6 Qxe6 {dooms the weak pawn on e5, according to
Tarrasch's terminology.} 18. Qe1 ({The pin created by the queen will prove
ineffective, but} 18. Re1 $6 {is even worse:} a4 19. Bc2 Bc5 20. Be3 Bxe3 21.
Rxe3 f4 22. Re1 f3 23. Bxe4 {Otherwise ...Ng5 with a decisive attack.} dxe4 24.
Rxe4 Qg6 $19) 18... Qxe5 19. f3 Bd6 $1 {Unpinning the knight with gain of time.
} 20. g3 Nc5 $17) 17... N4c5 18. Bc2 g6 19. Be3 f4 20. Bf2 a4 $11 {After
preventing the bishop's return to b3, Black may soon play ...Nxd4 followed by .
..Ne6 and ...c6-c5.}) 15... b4 {Apart from its known virtues, this attacks c3.}
16. cxb4 {A practical decision, allowing White to develop his queen's bishop.}
(16. c4 $2 {simply loses a pawn to} dxc4 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 $17) (16. Qd3 {runs into
} Nc5) (16. Qc2 {avoids the fork but also releases the pressure in the centre,
allowing Black to increase his space advantage.} bxc3 17. bxc3 c5 18. Nxe6 Qxe6
$1 ({Black plans ...Nc6, ...c5-c4, ...Bc5, with a strong initiative.} 18...
Nxe6 {looks more thematic, but after} 19. Rd1 {the pin along the d-file
prevents ...c5-c4, forcing the knight to abandon the blocking square with} Nc7
$11) 19. c4 {The only way to cross Black's plans.} d4 {Under different
circumstances, this way of blocking Black's centre may even favour White, but
introductory pawn play on the the queenside has weakened the squares b4 and c3,
offering Black an advantage.} 20. Nxd4 {Otherwise ...Nc6 with a clear
advantage.} Qxe5 21. Nf3 Qxa1 22. Bb2 Qxf1+ 23. Kxf1 Nc6 $15 {Black has a
small material advantage and controls the weak squares d4 and b4. Besides, the
light-squared bishop is passive.}) 16... Bxb4 17. Bg5 $1 {The point behind the
previous move. The bishop obtained this square for development, and now
threatens to weaken the defence of c6 (and, indirectly, d5) with Bxd8.} Kh8 {
Removing the king from the dangerous diagonal.} 18. Rc1 c5 $6 {Having the
better structure, Black did not need to rush.} (18... Rc8 {was better, and
after a neutral move like} 19. h4 {he could have prepared ...c6-c5 with} Bg8
$17) 19. Nxe6 Nxe6 20. Bxd5 N4xg5 21. Bxa8 Qxd1 22. Rfxd1 Rxa8 23. Nxg5 Nxg5 {
White has managed to destroy Black's central pawn chain, but the minor pieces
are not weaker than the rook. The bishop is stable and the final evaluation is
determined by the knight's fate. White will play well for a while, maintaining
equality.} 24. Rd6 {Preventing ...Ne6-d4.} Kg8 25. Rcd1 a5 26. Kf1 (26. f4 {
was also possible, as the knight activity in the centre after} Ne4 {does not
lead to more than equality:} 27. Rd8+ Rxd8 28. Rxd8+ Kf7 29. Rd7+ Kg6 30. Rc7
c4 $5 ({A neutral move such as} 30... h5 {would also lead to a draw, as White
cannot think of a constructive and active plan.}) 31. Rc6+ Kh5 32. Rxc4 Bc5+
33. Kh1 {Forced, due to the possible fork on d2.} Nf2+ {with a perpetual check.
}) 26... f4 27. h4 Nf7 {The knight has on a different square than e6, but it
remains an active piece, attacking e5 and preventing Rd8+.} 28. Re6 Kf8 29. Ke2
Re8 {Black decides to force the rook exchange himself, in order to weaken e5.}
30. Rxe8+ Kxe8 31. e6 Ne5 ({Or if} 31... Nd8 32. Rd6 $11) 32. Rd6 $2 {Only
this passive move, offering Black a tempo for nothing, creates problems for
White.} ({It was essential to drive the knight away from e5 in order to clear
the king's path.} 32. Rd5 $1 Nc6 33. Kd3 Nd4 34. Re5 Ke7 35. Ke4 g6 {Defending
f5 in order to meet Kf4 with ...Nxe6 without fearing the pin.} 36. Kd5 Nf5 $11
{None of the players has ovious ways to make progress.}) 32... c4 $1 $17 {
The threat ...Nd3 is very strong, as White is not in time to defend the f2-
and b2-pawns.} 33. Ra6 Nd3 34. Ra7 Nxb2 35. Rxg7 h6 36. Rc7 c3 37. g4 fxg3 38.
fxg3 Nxa4 {The weaknesses created by a2-a4, ...b5-b4 have cost White dearly.}
39. Kd1 Nc5 40. Rc6 Ke7 41. g4 Nxe6 0-1

