{In the comments to a previous game I have mentioned the plan based on b2-b4.
In that case, White did not want to allow ...a6-a5, with some pressure along
the a-file. But under certain circumstances, the central break ...d5-d4 may be
even stronger, up to the extent that it refutes White's concept.} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Nbd2
Nc5 10. c3 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Bc2 Qd7 13. Re1 Rd8 {Black has delayed his
kingside development in order to prepare ...d5-d4 under the best circumstances.
White thought that his next move would inhibit it, probably overlooking a
small tactical detail.} 14. b4 $2 ({The best reaction here is} 14. Nb3 Ne6 15.
Bf5 $14 {, undermining Black's control over d4. Due to the early ...Rd8, Black
does not have the resource from the next example.}) 14... Ne6 15. Nb3 {Given
the time, White would play a2-a4xb5, followed by Bd3, attacking b5, which
would force Black to either retreat with his knight or play ...Rb8, both
making the central break improbable and consolidating White's control in the
centre.} d4 $1 ({It's now or never! After} 15... Be7 $6 16. a4 d4 17. axb5 axb5
18. Be4 $14 {Black cannot free himself as the same trick as in the game does
not work anymore:} dxc3 $2 19. Qxd7+ Kxd7 20. Rd1+ Kc8 21. Bxc6 $3 Rxd1+ 22.
Kh2 {followed by Ra8 mate! It is never redunding to mention what a big
influence a2-a4 can have over the evaluation of the position.}) 16. Be4 {
The standard answer, which is not sufficient here, though.} (16. cxd4 {allows}
Bxb4 $17 {, developing with gain of time and followed by ...Ncxd4.}) (16. g4
Bg6 17. Nbxd4 {does not change much:} Ncxd4 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Bxb4 20. Re2
Qxd4 21. Qxd4 Rxd4 $17 {With an extra pawn and a normal position for Black.
The exchange on g6 at any time would only leave the pawn on h3 hanging after ..
. hxg6.}) 16... dxc3 $1 {White must have underestimated this move, which
weakens White's queenside and grabs a pawn on the way.} (16... d3 $2 {would be
a typical mistake, as it stabilizes White's position and leaves Black's minor
pieces without clear targets.} 17. a4 $1 {Of course!} (17. Re3 $22 Nxe5 18. g4
Nxf3+ 19. Qxf3 Bg6 20. Bc6 $18 {Chekhov}) 17... Be7 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra6 Nb8 {
A sad move to make.} 20. Ra5 $5 {The exchange sacrfice on e6 would also be
very strong, but this move is simpler. The knight cannot return to play due to
the hanging pawn on b5.} O-O 21. Re3 Nf4 22. Bd2 {In the long run, there is
nothing that can save the pawn on d3.}) 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. a3 {This offers
Black a free tempo and is equivalent with surrendering, but there is nothing
better.} ({The point behind Black's last move is that after} 18. Rd1+ Kc8 {
Black saves his knight on c6.} 19. Rxd8+ ({Or if} 19. Be3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Nxe5
$19 {Chekhov}) 19... Ncxd8 20. a3 c5 $17 {With an extra pawn and the
initiative on the queenside.}) 18... Bxf3 19. gxf3 {Trying to slow down
Black's initiative but ruining his own structure.} ({If} 19. Bxf3 Ncd4 20. Nxd4
Nxd4 21. Rd1 Ke6 $17 {White does not have any compensation for the lost pawn.})
19... g5 $1 {A typical way to block the double pawns. The pawn on e5 is
chronically weak and Black threatens ...Nxe5.} ({As pointed out by Chekhov,} 
19... Nxe5 $2 20. f4 Nc4 21. f5 $16 {would offer White a strong initiative.})
20. Bxg5 $6 {A small combination, aimed at connecting rooks in order to
retrieve the knight on c6. But giving up the dark-squared bishop accentuates
the weaknesses on the dark squares.} Nxg5 21. Rad1+ Kc8 {We can say that Black
has castled long now.} ({This is good enough, but the centralizing} 21... Ke6 {
may have been even stronger:} 22. Bxc6 Nxh3+ 23. Kh2 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Nf4 25. Re1
Rg8 26. Nd4+ Ke7 27. Nf5+ Kd8 28. Rc1 {White's initiative has reached a dead
end and it is Black's turn to attack.} Rg5 29. Ng3 Bg7 $19) 22. Bxc6 Bh6 $1 {
Suddenly, the c-pawn becomes threatening.} 23. Kg2 c2 24. Rc1 Rhg8 25. Kh1 ({
What else? If} 25. Rxc2 Rd3 $1 {threatens both ...Rxb3 and ...Nxf3+.} 26. Re3
Ne6+ {just wins material:} (26... Nxf3+ $6 27. Kxf3 Bxe3 28. fxe3 Rxb3 29. Bd5
Rxa3 30. Bxf7 Rf8 31. e6 Kd8 32. Ke4 $132) 27. Kf1 Bxe3 28. fxe3 Rxb3 $19)
25... Rd3 26. Nc5 Rxf3 ({Quite elegant, but the simpler} 26... Rd2 $19 {
also wins.}) 27. Rxc2 ({Chekhov gives the following line:} 27. Bxf3 Nxf3 28.
Rf1 Bxc1 29. Rxc1 Rg1+ 30. Rxg1 Nxg1 31. Nd3 Ne2 $19) 27... Rxh3+ 28. Kg2 Rxa3
{Black has won two pawns and his attack continues.} 29. Re3 Ne4+ 30. Kf3 Bxe3
31. Nxe4 Bh6+ 32. Ke2 Bf4 33. Rc5 Rd8 34. Bd5 Bxe5 0-1

