{The line played in the next game is very similar to the one above, but White
will play b2-b4 under different circumstances.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. c3 Nc5 10. Bc2 Bg4 11.
Re1 Be7 12. Nbd2 Qd7 {The main difference between this and the similar
position from the previous game is that Black has played ...Be7 instead of ...
Rd8. While this delayed the moment of ...d5-d4 (as the game went, for quite a
few dozens of moves) it offers Black more flexibility against White's plan
recommended above. The missing h2-h3, ...Bh5 is not relevant, as these moves
will happen later.} 13. Nb3 ({In the absence of the immediate threat of ...
d5-d4, the strongest plan is} 13. Nf1 $1 Rd8 14. Ne3 Bh5 15. b4 Ne6 16. g4 Bg6
17. Nf5 {This was played for the first time by Hjartarson against Kortschnoj
and cast a dark shadow over the whole variation. Quite sadly, I could not make
it work for the theoretical database.}) 13... Ne6 14. h3 Bh5 15. Bf5 {Karpov's
play looks logical: White fights for the c5-square. But the next move proves
to be an adequate antidote.} Ncd8 $1 {Black simply prepares to retake on e6
with the reserve knight, thus keeping his influence over c5 and d4 intact.} 16.
Be3 a5 $5 {Not giving White any time to organize the invasion on c5 with all
the comfort.} 17. Bc5 a4 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Nbd2 (19. Nbd4 $5 {is more active,
but Black is doing fine here, too.} Nxd4 20. cxd4 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 g6 {Forcing
the bishop to release the pressure against e6, in order to install a blocking
knight there.} 22. Bd3 (22. Bg4 $5 {is interesting, but not dangerous:} h5 23.
Qf6 $1 Rf8 24. Bf3 c6 {Black's king is entirely safe in the centre and ...Ne6
will soon happen anyway.}) 22... c6 23. Rac1 Ra6 24. Qe3 Ne6 {Threatening ...
Qa7 or ...Qb4.} 25. Bf1 O-O $11 {White still has to care about ...Qb4 with a
double attack. Black can soon play ... f7-f5, when his pawns on the light
squares will restrict the enemy bishop.}) 19... c6 $5 {A slightly mysterious
move in a position where Black has no problems at all. Kortschnoj obviously
did not want to hurry castling and simply consolidates his position, inviting
his opponent to show his cards. This method was rather typical for Karpov
himself, frequently provoking the opponents' mistakes, but now roles seem to
have changed as Kortschnoj used to be more straightforward.} ({Or maybe this
was a subtle way of preparing the next move? In this case, Kortschnoj's
approach must be considered "very concrete"! The point is that the immediate} 
19... Ng5 $2 {runs into} 20. g4 {, and if} g6 21. Bd7+ $3 Kxd7 22. Nxg5 Qxg5
23. Ne4 $18 {followed by Qxd5+. After 19...c6 this resource will not be
available anymore.}) (19... O-O $11 {would also be entirely fine for Black.})
20. b4 {At this point, Karpov's last move is mainly defensive. He probably
feared ... b5-b4, but he must also have hoped that in the long run he would
take control over the important d4-square. As we will see, this was not meant
to happen.} Ng5 21. Qe2 ({With the d5-pawn defended,} 21. g4 $2 {can be safely
answered with} g6 {If} 22. Bc2 Nxh3+ {wins two pawns.}) (21. h4 {deserves
mention, too. If} Bxf3 22. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 23. Qxf3 Ne6 ({White gets a strong
initiative after} 23... Qxh4 24. e6 $1) 24. g3 g6 25. Bh3 {[%csl Gb7,Gf8,Gg1,
Gg8][%cal Gh3e6] Black is solid, but only White can be slightly better.}) (21.
h4 {But Black can do better with} g6 $1 {, preventing the bishop's retreat to
h3. After} 22. hxg5 gxf5 23. Qc2 Bg6 {followed by ...h7-h6, Black has
excellent attacking chances.}) 21... g6 22. Bg4 Bxg4 23. hxg4 Nde6 {The second
knight steps on the blocking square.} 24. Qe3 h5 $1 {Suddenly White
experiences some problems along the h-file.} 25. Nxg5 Qxg5 26. Qxg5 Nxg5 27.
gxh5 ({The seemingly active} 27. f4 $6 Ne6 28. f5 {leaves White's daring pawns
hanging after} Ng7 $15) 27... Rxh5 28. Nf1 Rh4 {Controlling d4 and dreaming of
invading through c4.} 29. Rad1 Ke7 30. f3 Ne6 31. Ne3 Rd8 {Things have cleared
up and Black has a small but persistent advantage. His main positional threat
is ...d5-d4 (preferably with a rook on c4), dooming White's entire queenside.
In principle, White should hold, but his position is unpleasant. Karpov had
won many such almost drawn endings, but now he will find himself on the
opposite side.} 32. Ng4 {Cutting the h4-rook's connection to the queenside.}
Ng5 {Possibly planning ...Ne4-g3-f5.} 33. Ne3 Ne6 34. Ng4 Ng7 {Being denied
the tactical manoeuvre ...Ne4-g3-f5, Kortschnoj chooses the alternate route.}
35. Ne3 Nf5 36. Nc2 $2 {The decisive mistake, allowing the rook's access to c4.
The ease Karpov collapsed with is surprising.} (36. Nxf5+ {would not have been
a satisfactory solution either:} gxf5 {[%cal Gh4c4,Ge7e6] Threatening ...Rc4
and ...Ke6 with annoying pressure.} 37. Rd4 f4 $17 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge7e6,
Gd8h8] Planning an invasion with ...R8h8 and Rh1+, combined with ...Ke6.} 38.
g3 $2 Rg8 39. g4 Rgh8 40. Rxf4 Rh1+ 41. Kf2 R8h2+ 42. Kg3 Rxe1 43. Kxh2 Rxe5
$19 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3,Rf4][%cal Ge5e2,Ya4a1] followed by ...Re2 and ..Rxa2.}) ({
The only way to stay in the game was} 36. Ng4 $1 {, after which Black does not
have anything better than} Ke6 {[%csl Ra2,Rb4,Rc3][%cal Rh4h8,Rd5d4] ,
followed by the regrouping ...Rhh8, ...Rd7, ...R8d8 and finally ...d5-d4.})
36... Rc4 37. Rd3 d4 $1 $19 ({With his flag hanging, Kortschnoj finds the
right move order. After} 37... Ng7 $6 {White could return to the right path
with} 38. Ne3 Rh4 39. Ng4 $15) 38. g4 Ng7 39. Nxd4 Ne6 40. Red1 Nxd4 41. cxd4
Rxb4 {The time trouble was over and the game was adjourned. White's central
majority is not dangerous as the black king is ready to slow it down, while
Black's majority will soon be unstoppable.} 42. Kf2 c5 43. d5 {Trying a
desperate counterattack.} (43. dxc5 Rxd3 44. Rxd3 Rb2+ $19 {is also hopeless.})
43... Rb2+ 44. Kg3 Rxa2 {Black has a decisive advantage and Kortschnoj's home
analysis after adjournment proved accurate enough.} 45. Re3 b4 46. e6 Ra3 47.
Re2 fxe6 48. Rxe6+ Kf7 49. Rde1 Rd7 50. Rb6 Rd3 51. Ree6 R3xd5 52. Rxg6 a3 53.
Rbf6+ Ke7 54. Re6+ Kf8 55. Ref6+ Ke7 56. Re6+ Kd8 57. Ra6 Rb7 58. Rg8+ Kc7 59.
Rg7+ Rd7 60. Rg5 b3 61. Rxc5+ Kb8 0-1

