{We already got so familiarized with the strength of a blocking knight on e6
that I cannot end this article other than with an example in which this will
remain the main theme until deep in the ending. The next and last game also
features the three crucial criteria of evaluation from Tarrasch'perspective.} 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 d4 11. Bxe6 Nxe6 12. Nb3 $6 {An interesting, but not
entirely sound experiment of the highly enterprising Hungarian grandmaster.
White hopes to force his opponent to give up his central ambitions.} dxc3 13.
Qc2 {With the obvious intention to gain control over the d-file with Rd1. The
pawn on b2 is taboo because the knight on c6 is hanging, as Keres would gladly
point out.} Qd5 $5 {This will eventually lead to a position full of small
tricks, typical for Tal.} ({But the simpler} 13... Nb4 14. Qxc3 c5 {, making
the b6-square available for the queen, would also offer Black excellent play.})
14. Rd1 $6 ({This will lead to trouble, but} 14. bxc3 Rd8 {is also comfortable
for Black.}) 14... Nb4 {Gaining an important tempo. Here we can already see
what Tarrasch meant when emphasizing Black's "minor piece activity", but the
best is still to come.} 15. Qe2 Qc4 $1 {A seemingly paradoxical but most
effective way to put Black's queenside majority into motion.} ({Tal rightly
refrains from the intermediate} 15... cxb2 $6 {, which only helps White
completing his development:} 16. Bxb2 Qc4 17. Qxc4 bxc4 18. Na5 $11 {Black
does not have any problems, but neither does White.}) 16. Qxc4 bxc4 {No, Paul
Petrovich, with all the due respect, Black's queenside is not weak, despite
the double pawns!} 17. Na5 Nc2 18. Rb1 Na3 $1 {The culmination of the knight's
journey. But actually, this only leads to a move repetition at this stage, and
the same idea will be more effective a bit later.} 19. Ra1 (19. bxa3 c2 {
is an exchange.}) 19... Nc2 20. Rb1 Rb8 21. Nxc4 Na3 $1 {The improved version
of the spectacular knight jump.} 22. Nxa3 Bxa3 23. Ne1 $1 {White displays big
efforts to maintain material equality. But the manoeuvre initiated by the last
move will only manage to simplify to a much worse, probably lost ending.} cxb2
24. Nc2 bxc1=Q 25. Rxb8+ Ke7 26. Rxc1 Rxb8 27. Nxa3 Rb2 28. Rc2 Rxc2 29. Nxc2
Kd7 {The tactical phase has cleared the position of all impurities. The knight
on e6 keeps White's kingside pawns under control and the passed pawn offers
Black a big advantage. One may remember that knight endings are evaluated in
the same way as pawn endings, with the difference that from a practical point
of view they are more complicated. What really makes things worse for White is
the rapid centralisation of the black king.} 30. g3 ({White is not in time to
prevent the black king's advance with} 30. Kf1 Kc6 31. Ke2 Kd5 32. Nb4+ Kc4 33.
Nd3 (33. Nxa6 Kb5 34. Nb8 Kb6 35. Ke3 Kb7 36. Nd7 Kc8 {traps the knight.})
33... Kc3 34. f4 h5 $5 {followed by ...g7-g6 and ...c5-c4.}) 30... c5 31. f4
Nd4 $1 {The knight clears the e6-square for the king while also preventing
f4-f5.} 32. Ne3 ({The pawn ending after} 32. Nxd4 cxd4 {is easily won for
Black:} 33. Kf2 Ke6 34. Ke2 Kd5 35. Kd3 h6 {White will soon exhaust his
neutral pawn moves and will have to allow ...Ke4. The point is that} 36. g4 g5
$1 {wins the e5-pan.}) 32... Ke6 33. Kf2 Nf5 34. Nd1 Kd5 $1 ({Black does not
have time for} 34... h5 {due to} 35. Nc3 {, setting up a barrier in front of
the black king.}) 35. g4 Nh6 36. Kf3 Kd4 37. Ne3 g6 38. g5 {Setting up a small
trap.} Ng8 $1 ({White might have hoped for} 38... Nf5 $2 {, when the pawn
ending is drawn:} 39. Nxf5+ gxf5 40. h4 Kd3 41. h5 c4 42. g6 $11) 39. Ng4 c4
40. Ke2 c3 {The pawn's advance is decisive.} 41. Kd1 Ne7 42. Nf6 Nf5 43. Kc1 a5
44. Nd7 (44. Nxh7 Kd3 {followed by ...Nd4-e2 wins quickly.}) 44... Ne3 45. Nb8
Kd3 46. Nc6 a4 47. Nd8 Nd5 48. e6 fxe6 (48... Nxf4 $1 {followed by ...Ne2+ and
c2+ was a quicker win. But the game move does not spoil anything, either.}) 49.
Nxe6 a3 50. Nc5+ Kc4 51. Ne4 Nb4 52. Kb1 Kd4 0-1

