1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 {Old theory evaluated this move as harmless, due to Black's
possibility to break in the centre at an early stage. The whole system came
into the limelight for the first time when Karpov used it during the Baguio
1978 and Merano 1981 world title matches against Kortschnoj. At that time,
this was intended to avoid the main lines, as Karpov systematically failed to
find anything convincing after 9.c3 Bc5. Further developments of Karpov's
ideas turned this variation into White's main weapon.} Nc5 10. c3 Be7 ({
Before 1978,} 10... d4 {was considered a simple antidote, but in Baguio and
Merano Kortschnoj learned that things are not that simple.} 11. Bxe6 ({In
Baguio Karpov unleashed the bomb} 11. Ng5 {, an idea of his second Igor
Zaitsev. Kortschnoj found a way to reach a slightly worse ending and drew. At
the current stage, Black seems to be doing fine here.}) 11... Nxe6 12. cxd4
Ncxd4 {In Merano Karpov was successful with both 13.Ne4 and} 13. a4 {, which
were novelties at that time. I have discarded this system for the present
article because I encountered some problems after the latter move.}) 11. Bc2 {
It does not make sense to delay the bishop retreat, as after making a
developing move Black threatens ...d5-d4 under improved circumstances.} (11.
Re1 $6 d4 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. cxd4 Ncxd4 {It is obvious that Re1 is not very
useful at this stage, while ...Be7 brings Black one move closer to get castled.
} 14. a4 {With Black's king close to safety, this is a blow into the wind.} (
14. Ne4 O-O 15. Be3 Nf5 16. Qc2 Nxe3 17. Rxe3 {In the main lines White takes
with the pawn, but this would make little sense with the rook on e1.} Qd5 $15 {
Black is well developed and exerts the usual control on the light squares.}) (
14. Nxd4 {activates Black's pieces.} Qxd4 15. Qc2 Qc5 16. Qe4 Rd8 17. Nf3 Qd5
18. Qc2 Bb4 19. Rf1 Bc5 20. Bg5 Qd3 21. Rac1 Qxc2 22. Rxc2 Rd3 23. Rfc1 Bb6 $17
{McShane,L (2592)-Ivanchuk, V (2787) Germany 2008 (0-1, 51)}) 14... O-O 15.
axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Qxa8 18. Ne4 Rd8 $15 {Timoshenko,G (2535)
-Krasenkow,M (2505) Moscow 1989 (В1/2-В1/2, 39)}) 11... d4 {This leads to
completely different play than in the lines with 10...d4. Black cannot
transfer his knight to e6 so easily, but the bishop is also a good stabilizer.
At the same time, the white bishop may have problems becoming active.} 12. Nb3
(12. Ne4 d3 13. Nxc5 dxc2 {transposes}) (12. cxd4 {[%emt 0:00:05] is examined
in Line 5}) 12... d3 13. Nxc5 {This simplifies to an ending that yields White
only a symbolic advantage. The most probable result is a draw.} ({The more
ambitious} 13. Bb1 {is examined in Lines 2 to 4.}) 13... dxc2 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {
Black needs to keep e5 under pressure.} (14... Nxd8 15. Nxe6 Nxe6 {reaches the
perfect blockade but leaves Black a pawn down after} 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Nxc5
18. Rfc1 {[%emt 0:00:43] Madl,I (2340)-Olsarova,T (2209) Germany 2014 (В1/2-В1/
2,}) 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Be3 {The only adequate way to complete the development.}
({The attempt to consolidate e5 with} 16. Bf4 $2 {offers Black a few free
tempi for developing his initiative.} Rf8 17. Bg3 g5 18. h3 h5 19. Rac1 h4 20.
Bh2 Rxf3 21. gxf3 Rd2 $19 {White is simply paralyzed, Yingrui,L (2031)-Garcia
Villalba, D (1827) Madrid 2017 (1-0, 34)}) 16... Rd5 {Black will get the
e5-pawn for the c2-pawn, when his weakness on e6 offers White rather symbolic
chances for a concrete advantage.} 17. Rfc1 (17. c4 {This makes part of
White's general plan, but played at this moment it looks premature:} bxc4 18.
Rac1 (18. Rfc1 {is less popular but it is a bit more restrictive. However, it
doesn't make the line satisfactory for White, either.} Nb4 19. a3 Nd3 20. Rxc2
Kd7 21. Nd2 {This is not playable in the mainline as the pawn on a3 would be
hanging in the end.} Nxb2 22. Nxc4 Nxc4 23. Rxc4 Rb8 24. Rac1 c5 25. f4 Kc6 {
and it is White who has to worry about maintaining equality, Harikrishna,P 
(2753)-Ding,L (2766) Huaian 2016 CBM 171 Extra [Besenthal,K] (0-1, 42)}) 18...
Nb4 19. a3 Nd3 20. Rxc2 Kd7 21. Bd4 ({As mentioned above} 21. Nd2 Nxb2 {
[%csl Ga3] leaves a3 hanging.}) 21... Rb8 {Black's activity is more relevant
than his minor structural defects. Besides, the king takes an active part in
the fight as it defends c7.} 22. Bc3 {In Hou,Y (2578)-Koneru,H (2600) Tirana
2011 (В1/2-В1/2, 58) Black lost her coordination starting with this moment. A
possible improvement was} ({White cannot maintain the status quo with, say,} 
22. h3 Bc5 23. Bc3 Rf8 $15 {Black is ready to build up his kingside initiative.
}) 22... Rdb5 23. Rd1 Kc8 24. Nd4 R5b6 $15 {followed by ...c7-c5 and keeping
White busy with defending b2.}) 17... Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. Rxc2 ({As much as
I tried, I could not understand why} 19. Bd4 {is a relatively popular move.}
Rg5 ({Years ago I analyzed this position with Jan Willem De Jong and suggested
} 19... Re2 $1 20. Kf1 Rd2 21. Be3 Rd1+ 22. Rxd1 cxd1=Q+ 23. Rxd1 {After
exchanging one rook Black should not be worried about his weakness at all.
Only weeks later Jan Willem played the following game, allowing him to win a
mini-match for a qualification spot:} Rf8 24. Ke2 Rf5 25. Rd4 h5 26. h3 Bf6 27.
Re4 Kd7 28. f4 Rd5 29. g4 g6 $11 {Pruijssers,R (2408)-De Jong,J (2445)
Hilversum 2008 (В1/2-В1/2, 82)}) 20. Rxc2 Kf7 21. Be3 Rd5 {This is the second
reason why I cannot understand 19.Bd4. Black just gets a free tempo to improve
the rook's placement.} (21... Re5 {was played in Carlsen,M (2844)-Ding,L (2766)
Wijk aan Zee 2016 CBM 171 [Marin,M] (В1/2-В1/2, 99) transposing below.}) 22. c4
bxc4 $6 {With the king far from c7 this is hard to understand.} ({Black should
just defend with} 22... Rd7 {, when the extra tempo ...Kf7 cannot harm.} 23.
cxb5 axb5 24. Rac1 Bd6 25. g3 Ra8 26. a3 Ra4 27. Rd2 Ke8 28. Rcd1 Rf7 $11) 23.
Rxc4 Bd6 24. b3 Rb8 25. Rac1 Ke7 26. Kf1 Kd7 27. Ke2 Rf8 {With some light
pressure for White in Nisipeanu,L (2668)-Svetushkin,D (2604) Predeal 2007 (1-0,
50)}) 19... Kf7 {I slightly prefer this over castling, as the king may be
needed to defend e6.} (19... Rd5 {, preparing to withdraw the rook, is an
important alternative.} 20. c4 Rd7 21. cxb5 ({Another game with a similar
course went} 21. Kf1 Kf7 22. Ke2 Rhd8 23. cxb5 axb5 24. a4 bxa4 25. Rxa4 Rb8
26. Rac4 Rb7 27. g3 {В1/2-В1/2 Azarov,S (2577)-Melkumyan,H (2653) Bad Wiessee
2016}) 21... axb5 22. a4 {White obviously does not believe in his advantage.
But more consistent play would also offer very little:} (22. g3 Kf7 23. Re1 Ra8
24. b3 Ra6 25. Kg2 Bd6 26. Rd1 Re7 27. Kf3 Re8 28. Ke4 Rea8 29. Rdd2 Ke7 30. f3
Ra5 31. g4 b4 32. Bd4 {В1/2-В1/2 Kukel,I (2316)-Lahner,J (2314) Czechia 2008})
(22. Rac1 Bd6 23. Rc6 Rf8 24. g3 Rf5 {This is one of the rare moments when it
is better to have the king on e8 instead of f7.} 25. Bc5 Be5 26. Rxe6+ Kf7 27.
Ra6 Bxb2 $11) 22... bxa4 23. g3 (23. Kf1 Kf7 24. Rxa4 Rb8 25. Rac4 c5 26. Bxc5
Bxc5 27. Rxc5 Rd1+ 28. Ke2 Rb1 29. g3 R1xb2 {Besenthal: Das wars dann...} 30.
Rxb2 Rxb2+ 31. Kf3 Rb3+ 32. Ke2 Rb2+ 33. Kf3 Rb3+ 34. Ke2 {1/2-1/2 (34)
Karjakin,S (2779)-Caruana,F (2804) Shamkir 2016 CBM 173 [Marin] Besenthal:
GemдЯ der Regeln fьr dieses Turnier ist ein Remis vor dem 40. Zug eigentlich
"verboten", doch in dieser Position wird der Schiedsrichter ein Einsehen
gehabt haben.}) 23... Kf7 24. Rxa4 Rb8 25. Rf4+ Ke8 ({Better than} 25... Bf6 {
, when in Abasov, N (2632) -Bacrot,E (2671) Douglas 2019 (В1/2-В1/2, 31) White
could have played on with} 26. b4) 26. Kg2 Rb4 $11) 20. c4 (20. g3 {is
harmless.} Rd8 21. a4 Red5 22. Kg2 Bc5 23. Bxc5 Rxc5 24. axb5 axb5 25. Re2 $11
{В1/2-В1/2 Klovans,J (2433) -Kortschnoj,V (2600) Arvier 2006}) (20. Kf1 Rd8 21.
a4 Bg5 22. Bd4 Red5 23. axb5 axb5 24. Ra7 R8d7 25. Ke2 c6 26. Rxd7+ Rxd7 27. b4
{Warmerdam,M (2433) -Stevic,H (2587) Skopje 2018 (В1/2-В1/2, 48)} e5 28. Bc5
Ke6 $11) (20. a4 Rd8 21. axb5 axb5 22. g3 Rd7 23. Ra7 Bc5 24. Bxc5 Rxc5 25. Rb7
Rdd5 {В1/2-В1/2 Stevic,H (2563)-Bacrot,E (2669) Zagreb 2019}) 20... b4 {
This is a small success for White, but in practice it did not prove enough to
generate realistic winning chances:} 21. Rd1 Rd8 22. Rxd8 Bxd8 23. Kf1 Bg5 24.
Bd4 Ra5 25. b3 Bf6 (25... e5 26. Ba7 e4 27. Ke2 Ke6 28. g3 h5 29. h4 Be7 30.
Be3 g6 31. Bd2 Bd6 32. a4 Rf5 33. Be3 c5 $11 {Volokitin,A (2634) -Brkic,A 
(2565) Austria 2019 (В1/2-В1/2, 40)}) 26. Be3 Bg5 27. f4 Be7 28. g4 h5 29. h3
g6 30. Ke2 hxg4 31. hxg4 e5 $11 {Carlsen,M (2844)-Ding,L (2766) Wijk aan Zee
2016 CBM 171 [Marin,M] (В1/2-В1/2, 99). And even Carlsen was unable to squeeze
anything out of this.} *

