1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. Nb3 d3 13. Bb1 {This is the most
ambitious reaction to Black's 11...d4. It leads to very tense play, involving
many concrete/tactical subtleties.} Nxb3 14. axb3 Bf5 {The plot is clear:
White needs to attack the pawn on d3 while Black has to use the available time
and space to build up his counterplay.} 15. b4 {The consequences of this move 
(now and later) are far from one-sided. White clears the a2-g8 diagonal for
his passive bishop and gets some control in the centre. But on the other hand,
he exposes the b-pawn to ...a7-a5 (and, as we will see, not only that).} ({
Another possible plan is} 15. Bf4 O-O 16. Ne1 (16. Qd2 {The brutish plan of
attacking d3 without any previous commitment runs into an elegant antidote.}
Qd5 17. b4 Qd7 $3 {Quite instructively, Black has spent a tempo on provoking
b2-b4.} 18. Rd1 a5 $11 {White does not have anything better than taking on d3
with comfortable play for Black, as} 19. bxa5 Nxa5 20. Bxd3 Nb3 $15 {loses an
exchange.}) 16... Qd5 17. Bxd3 (17. Nxd3 Rfd8 $19) 17... Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Qxb3 19.
Qf3 ({Golubev recomends} 19. Nf3 $1 Rfd8 20. Qe4 Qe6 21. Rfc1 {Preparing Nd4.
But Black has several ways to retain good play, for instance} a5 22. Nd4 Nxd4
23. cxd4 Qd7 24. Be3 a4 $11 {White's centre looks impressive, but Black can
get a far-advanced passed pawn on a3 at any time.}) 19... Qe6 20. Nd3 Rfd8 21.
Rad1 Rd7 $1 $15 {White starts experiencing problems, Sengupta,D (2567)-Wei,Y 
(2706) Tsaghkadzor 2015 (0-1, 43).}) (15. Re1 {[%emt 0:00:03] is examined in
Line 3.}) (15. Be3 {is examined in Line 4. Now is a good moment to say that
most these lines can transpose to each other. In the current line we examine
only games in which White does not play Re1 or Be3 at an early stage.}) 15...
O-O 16. Bf4 Qd7 17. h3 {A slow positional plan. White will force the bishop to
abandon the optimal f5-square, from which it defends the pawn and controls the
important square e6.} Rfd8 18. g4 Bg6 19. Bg3 {Still regrouping.} ({For far
from obvious reasons at this stage,} 19. Re1 {allows Black to start his
counterplay.} a5 20. bxa5 Rxa5 21. e6 {In the mainline after 19.Bf4 instead of
19.Re1 this would be crushing, but here it does not work.} (21. Ba2 Rf8 22. e6
Qd8 23. exf7+ Kh8 24. b4 {Panitevsky, I (2390)-Ivanov, B (2429) ICCF email
2015 (В1/2-В1/2, 24)} Ra4 $11 {Black has kept his pawn on d3 and the pawn on
f7 is not really menacing. Black will retrieve it later. In the meanwhile both
White's wings are weak.}) 21... fxe6 22. Rxa5 Nxa5 23. Ne5 Qd5 24. Nxg6 hxg6
25. Bxc7 d2 $1 {This is the point. White gains a tempo to save the pride of
his position.} 26. Rf1 Nc4 ({This leads to entertaining play, but the simpler} 
26... Ra8 {is also good.} 27. Bxa5 Rxa5 28. Bxg6 Bd6 $11 {The pawn on d2
restricts White and the king on g1 faces the threat ...Qe5.}) 27. Bxd8 Nxb2 28.
Qc2 Bxd8 29. Qxg6 Kf8 30. Bc2 Qe5 31. Bb3 Bc7 32. Kg2 Nc4 $5 $44 {Just one of
the many good continuations.} 33. Bxc4 $2 Qh2+ 34. Kf3 Qxh3+ 35. Ke2 Qxf1+ 36.
Kxf1 d1=Q+ 37. Kg2 bxc4 $19) 19... h5 $1 {The natural way to start Black's
counterplay.} (19... a5 $2 {does not work with the white rook on f1.} 20. bxa5
Rxa5 (20... b4 21. a6) 21. e6 fxe6 22. Rxa5 Nxa5 23. Ne5 Qe8 24. Nxg6 hxg6 25.
Bxc7 Ra8 26. Bxd3 Nc4 27. Qe2 $18) 20. Nd2 {Deviating from a previous game of
Mamedyarov.} (20. Re1 d2 21. Re2 Bxb1 22. Rxb1 (22. Rxd2 {prevents ...Qxf5 but
transposes to the game anyway.} Qe6 23. Rxb1 hxg4 24. hxg4 Qxg4) 22... hxg4 23.
Rxd2 Qf5 24. hxg4 Qxg4 {Black is very active already and White should think of
a way to maintain equality.} 25. Nd4 $2 (25. Rxd8+ Rxd8 26. Qe2 Bh4 27. Kg2 Ne7
28. e6 fxe6 29. Re1 {offers White reasonable compensation for the pawn.}) (25.
Kg2 Rxd2 26. Nxd2 (26. Qxd2 Nxe5 $1 $17 27. Nxe5 Qe4+) 26... Qg6 $11) (25. Ra1
Rxd2 26. Nxd2 Qxd1+ 27. Rxd1 Rd8 $15) 25... Qe4 $1 (25... Qg6 {exposes the
queen, allowing White to reach equality:} 26. Nxc6 Qxc6 27. Ra1 Qg6 $11 {
Anand, V (2776)-Mamedyarov,S (2761) Moscow 2016 (В1/2-В1/2, 37)}) 26. Ra1 (26.
Nxc6 {does not work with the queen on e4:} Rxd2 27. Nxe7+ Kf8 28. Qxd2 Qxb1+
29. Kg2 Kxe7 $19) (26. Re2 Qg6 $15) 26... Nxd4 27. Rxd4 Rxd4 28. Qxd4 Qxd4 29.
cxd4 Bxb4 $15) 20... hxg4 ({As paradoxical as it may seem,} 20... h4 $5 {
deserves being mentioned. True, Black releases the pressure on g4, but he puts
the enemy king in a delicate situation.} 21. Bh2 a5 22. f4 axb4 23. Rxa8 Rxa8
24. f5 (24. cxb4 Qd4+ 25. Kg2 Nxb4 26. f5 Bh7 $19) 24... bxc3 25. bxc3 Bh7 {
A very difficult position to evaluate. The bishop is caged in on h7, but
White's king is exposed and the bishop on b1 needs some effort to return into
play, too.} 26. Nf3 {may be the critical test to Black's plan.} (26. Rf3 Qd5
27. Bxd3 Nxe5 28. Bxe5 Qxe5 $19 {The king's vulnerability is decisive. Black
can later free his bishop with ...g7-g6 or ...Kg8 and ...f7-f6.}) (26. Qf3 b4
27. cxb4 Bxb4 28. Bf4 Bc3 {wins the pawn on e5, ensuring Black against any
problems.}) (26. Ne4 b4 27. Qxd3 (27. cxb4 Nxb4 $19 {leaves the b1-bishop as
caged as his rival.}) 27... Qxd3 28. Bxd3 bxc3 29. Rc1 Ra3 30. Rxc3 Rxc3 31.
Nxc3 Bc5+ 32. Kg2 Bd4 $11) 26... b4 27. Qxd3 Qxd3 28. Bxd3 Ra3 29. Be4 Rxc3 {
Black has won a pawn but White is well coordinated and the bishop is still
arrested on h7.} 30. Ra1 Na7 31. Kg2 Ra3 32. Rd1 Nb5 33. Rd7 Ra2+ 34. Kf1 Ra1+
35. Kf2 Ra2+ 36. Ke1 Ra1+ 37. Kd2 Ra2+ 38. Kc1 {Black may be in trouble. If he
does not find an improvement somewhere along this line he should discard ...
h5-h4.}) 21. hxg4 Nxb4 $1 {The best idea. Black intends to cage the bishop
with ...c5-c4.} (21... a5 {does not work now as the king has the h2-square.}
22. f4 (22. bxa5 Rxa5 23. Rxa5 Nxa5 24. f4 Nc4) 22... axb4 23. Rxa8 Rxa8 24. f5
bxc3 25. bxc3 Bh7 26. Rf3 $16) 22. cxb4 Bxb4 23. Ba2 c5 24. e6 {The best
chance for counterplay.} fxe6 25. Nf3 c4 26. Ne5 Qe8 {Statically, Black is
doing great as White's extra piece exists only on paper. But White has some
chances on the kingside.} 27. Kg2 (27. Qf3 Rac8 28. Kg2 Rd4 {with the
initiative.}) 27... Be4+ $1 {The best regrouping.} (27... Rd5 28. f3 $2 (28.
Qf3 $1 {was better, in order to consolidate the knight after} Ra7 29. Qe3 $14)
28... Rad8 (28... Bd6 $1 29. Nxg6 Bxg3 30. Kxg3 Qxg6 $17) 29. Rh1 (29. Qc1 Bd6
30. Qg5 d2 {is complicated.}) 29... Bd6 30. Qe1 d2 31. Qe3 Bc2 $19 {Caruana,F 
(2822)-Mamedyarov,S (2801) Saint Louis 2018 (1-0, 56)}) 28. f3 Bb7 29. Rh1 Bd6
30. Qe1 Bxe5 31. Bxe5 Qg6 {Black has cleared the position from any
"impurities" and the mutual attacks keep the position balanced. Here is a
possible continuation:} 32. Qh4 Rd5 33. Bc3 Rf5 34. Raf1 e5 35. b3 Rxf3 $1 36.
Rxf3 Bxf3+ 37. Kxf3 Rf8+ 38. Kg3 Qe4 39. Qh8+ Kf7 40. Rf1+ Qf4+ $1 41. Rxf4+
exf4+ 42. Kxf4 Rxh8 43. bxc4 Rh2 44. Bb3 Ke7 45. cxb5 axb5 $11 *

