1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. Nb3 d3 13. Bb1 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bf5 15.
Re1 {This move is useful in many setups, but we know already that it exposes
the rook to ...d3-d2.} O-O 16. b4 {A familiar plan.} ({Here is another example
of Black losing a tempo to provoke b3-b4:} 16. Be3 Qd5 17. b4 (17. Bd4 {
transposes to line 4.}) 17... Qd7 18. h3 (18. Ba2 {offered Black an instant
initiative:} a5 19. bxa5 Rxa5 20. b4 {Weinitschke,G-Kroener,O DDR 1974 (В1/
2-В1/2, 73)} Ra4 $1 {Planning ...R8a8.} 21. Bb3 Rxa1 22. Qxa1 Be4 23. Nd2 Bd5
$15) 18... Rfd8 19. g4 Bg6 {It appears that White's extra tempo Be3 is not too
useful as it makes the thematic e4-e5 irrelevant.} 20. Bd4 (20. Bf4 {
transposes to the mainline.}) 20... Bxb4 {In this position the extra tempo is
b3-b4 (compare to Line 4) and once again it offers Black additional
possibilities. This is a good moment to repeat that b3-b4 can be useful only
under certain circumstances.}) 16... Qd7 (16... Qd5 $2 {runs straight into
White's plan:} 17. h3 Rfd8 18. g4 Be6 (18... Bg6 19. Ba2 Qd7 20. e6 $16) 19.
Re3 $16 {Karjakin,S (2723)-Mamedyarov,S (2719) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009 CBM 134 
[Karjakin,S] (1-0, 52)}) 17. h3 ({White has an alternative (but so far rare)
plan:} 17. Bf4 Rfd8 18. h4 (18. h3 {transposes to the main game}) 18... h6 19.
Re3 a5 {Starting counterplay before White's kingside attack becomes real.} 20.
bxa5 Rxa5 (20... Nxa5 {is also possible:} 21. e6 fxe6 22. Nd4 Nc4 23. Rxa8 Rxa8
24. Nxf5 exf5 25. Rxd3 Qe6 $13) 21. Rxa5 Nxa5 22. Nd4 Nc4 23. Nxf5 $5 Nxe3 $1 {
A correct sacrifice, keeping the d-pawn and active play as compensation for
the material.} (23... Qxf5 24. Rxd3 Rxd3 25. Qxd3 Qxd3 26. Bxd3 Bxh4 27. b3 Na5
28. Bxb5 Nxb3 29. Be3 $14 {Black should be able to hold this, but playing
against two bishops and the white space advantage may be unpleasant.}) 24. Nxe3
c5 25. b3 Bxh4 26. c4 Qd4 27. g3 bxc4 28. bxc4 Bg5 29. Nf5 Qc3 $13 {
Kasimdzhanov, R (2703)-Wei,Y (2694) Tashkent 2016 (0-1, 48)}) 17... Rfd8 18. g4
({White could also try playing with the black bishop on f5, in the hope that
it will be vulnerable to Nd4. But a recent top level game showed that Black
can keep his own.} 18. Bf4 {transposes to the main game} a5 19. bxa5 (19. g4
Bg6 {transposes below}) 19... Rxa5 20. Rxa5 Nxa5 21. Nd4 g5 {It is the time
for Black to display territorial ambitions.} 22. b4 Nc4 23. Bc1 d2 $1 {Winning
an exchange but for good compensation.} 24. Bxf5 dxe1=Q+ 25. Qxe1 Qd5 26. e6
Qe5 27. exf7+ Kxf7 28. Be4 Re8 {White should now hurry using the favourable
moment, with the h7-pawn hanging, to force a draw:} 29. Nf3 Qe6 30. Nd4 Qe5 31.
Nf3 Qe6 32. Nd4 {В1/2-В1/2 Svidler,P (2745)-Mamedyarov,S (2743) Reykjavik 2015}
) 18... Bg6 19. Bf4 (19. Ba2 {is best met with} Kh8 (19... Qc8 {Shirov,A (2689)
-Mamedyarov,S (2743) Reykjavik 2015 (0-1, 98)} 20. Bg5 $5) 20. Bf4 Rf8 {
With e5-e6 in the air (actually White's only plan) it is a good idea to place
the rook on the f-file, clearing the d8-square for the queen at the same time.}
(20... a5 $6 21. e6 $1) 21. Bg3 (21. e6 fxe6 22. Bxe6 Qd8 23. Bg3 Bd6 $11)
21... f5 $2 {But that is going too far.} (21... a5 22. bxa5 Rxa5 23. e6 Qd8 24.
exf7 b4 $11) 22. exf6 Bxf6 23. Be6 Qd8 24. Re3 a5 25. h4 axb4 26. Rxa8 Qxa8 27.
h5 bxc3 28. bxc3 Be8 29. Qxd3 $16 {Saric,I (2660)-Al Sayed,M (2524) Biel 2016 
(1-0, 35) As we see, it is only White who benefited from the opening of the
kingside.}) 19... a5 20. bxa5 ({This is the most restrictive move order, as
after} 20. Ba2 Qc8 21. bxa5 {, as in Bulmaga,I (2412)-Heinemann,J (2294)
Erfurt 2017 (В1/2-В1/2, 49), Black could have used the absence of pressure
along the a-file with} Nxa5 {, for instance} 22. e6 f6 23. b4 Nc4 24. Bxc4 bxc4
25. Rxa8 Qxa8 26. Bxc7 Rc8 27. Bf4 Be4 $15 {White's extra pawn is not relevant
while his king is weak and Black's space advantage annoying.}) 20... Rxa5 21.
Ba2 ({Starting the kingside attack with the bishop on b1 does not promise much:
} 21. Rxa5 Nxa5 22. e6 fxe6 23. Ne5 Qd5 24. Nxg6 hxg6 25. Bxc7 d2 26. Rf1 Nc4
27. Bxd8 Nxb2 28. Bxe7 (28. Qc2 Bxd8 29. Qxb2 d1=Q $11 30. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 31. Kg2
Qd5+ 32. f3 Qd1 $11) 28... Nxd1 29. Rxd1 Qb3 $19 {Timofeev,A (2564)-Reshef,O 
(2402) Jerusalem 2015 (В1/2-В1/2, 42)}) 21... Rf8 $1 {The familiar and best
reaction to the threat e5-e6.} (21... Qc8 22. b4 Ra6 23. e6 f6 24. Bb3 Rxa1 25.
Qxa1 Kh8 26. h4 $14) (21... Rda8 22. e6 Qd8 23. exf7+ Kh8 24. Ng5 Qf8 (24...
Rxa2 25. Rxa2 Rxa2 26. Qf3 Ra6 27. Ne6 Qa8 28. Nxc7 Ra1 29. Bc1 $14) 25. Qf3
Bxg5 26. Bxg5 Bxf7 27. Qxc6 Rxa2 28. Rxa2 Rxa2 29. Qxb5 h6 30. Bd2 Qd6 31. c4
Kg8 32. Bc3 $14) 22. b4 (22. e6 {is not dangerous now:} Qd8 23. exf7+ Bxf7 24.
Bxf7+ Rxf7 25. Qb3 Kf8 {[%csl Gf3,Gf4]}) 22... Ra4 23. Qd2 $2 {Strangely
enough, Caruana did not know (or forgot) how important it is to prevent Black
from installing a blocking knight on e6.} ({Even though} 23. e6 {does not seem
to offer an advantage, this should have been automatically played.} Qd8 24.
exf7+ Kh8 25. Bg3 h6 {[%cal Ge7f6]} 26. h4 Bd6 $132) 23... Nd8 $15 {The knight
will soon reach e6, offering Black great play.} 24. Bg5 c5 25. Bxe7 Qxe7 26.
bxc5 Qxc5 27. Nh4 Ne6 $15 {Caruana,F (2805)-Giri,A (2773) Stavanger 2015 (В1/
2-В1/2, 43)} *

