1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. Nb3 d3 13. Bb1 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bf5 15.
Be3 O-O 16. Bd4 Qd5 17. Re1 (17. Bxd3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Qxb3 19. Qe4 Qe6 20. Be3 (
20. Rfd1 a5 21. Be3 a4) 20... f5 21. Qf4 a5 22. Rfd1 Rfd8 23. h4 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1
Rd8 25. Re1 Rd5 26. Bc1 Rd8 27. Be3 Rd5 28. Bc1 {1/2-1/2 (28) Frolyanov,D 
(2599)-Vokarev,S (2431) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011} h6 29. h5 a4 30. c4 Rc5 31. cxb5
Rc4 32. Qg3 Rg4 33. Qh3 Na7) 17... d2 $1 {This was known in the late '80s
already, but became popular only decades later. Black intends to exchange his
vulnerable pawn for one of White's.} 18. Re2 (18. Bxf5 $5 {is an interesting
exchange sacrifice.} dxe1=Q+ 19. Qxe1 Qxb3 20. Qb1 $2 ({White should have
understood that this was the last moment when the typical break} 20. e6 $1 {
was possible.} Nxd4 21. Nxd4 Qxb2 22. exf7+ Kh8 23. Rb1 Qa3 $13) 20... g6 21.
Be4 Qe6 {White's compensation is very uncertain now.} 22. Qa2 Nxd4 23. Bxa8 Nb3
24. Bd5 Qxd5 25. Nd4 Qxe5 26. Qxb3 Bc5 $17 {Amonatov,F (2559)-Svetushkin,D 
(2588) Moscow 2007 (0-1, 51)}) (18. Qxd2 Bxb1 19. Raxb1 Qxb3 {equalizes.
White's attempt to take over the initiative at any cost with} 20. e6 {
eventually left him a pawn down with insufficient compensation:} fxe6 21. Re4
Rad8 22. Qe2 Bf6 23. Rxe6 Nxd4 24. Nxd4 Bxd4 25. cxd4 Rxd4 26. Re7 Qd5 27. h3
c5 $15 {Brkic,A (2521)-Iordachescu,V (2584) Plovdiv 2008 (0-1, 48)}) 18... Bxb1
19. Rxb1 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 (20. cxd4 Bb4 {allows Black to consolidate his pawn.
Due to the threat ...c7-c5 White would be forced to give up his d4-pawn for
removing the intruder.}) 20... Bg5 {Black defends his pawn, but the bishop is
less stable here than in the line above, so the struggle continues.} 21. g3 {
A slow but consistent continuation.} (21. Nf3 Bf4 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gg2g3]} 22.
Nxd2 Rad8 23. Qc2 Bxe5 $11) (21. h4 Bf4 22. b4 (22. g3 Bxe5 23. Rxd2 Bf6 24.
Qc2 Rfe8 25. Rbd1 g6 26. b4 Rad8 $11 {Bacrot,E (2697)-Aguera Naredo,J (2375)
Skopje 2015 (В1/2-В1/2, 44)}) 22... Bxe5 23. Rxd2 Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Qf5 25. Ra1 Qf6
26. g3 Rad8 27. Rd7 h6 28. Qd2 Rfe8 29. Rd1 Rxd7 30. Qxd7 Re2 31. Qd8+ Qxd8 32.
Rxd8+ Kh7 33. Rd7 f6 34. Rxc7 Rxb2 $11 {1/2-1/2 (53) Alekseenko,K (2650)
-Nesterov,A (2423) Yaroslavl 2019}) 21... c5 22. Nf5 Qd3 23. Nd6 Qg6 {
Indirectly pinning the g-pawn.} 24. h4 (24. Kh1 $5 f6 $5 $132) 24... Bf4 {
This one is my favourite continuation among the three that offer chances to
reach equality. Black attacks e5 and in some cases will be ready to sacrifice
on g3 for a perpetual.} (24... Bh6 25. h5 $1 (25. Kh2 f6 26. e6 Rad8 27. e7
Rxd6 28. exf8=Q+ Kxf8 $44 {Stellwagen,D (2605)-Svetushkin,D (2588) Dresden
2008 (В1/2-В1/2, 41)}) 25... Qxh5 26. Rxd2 Qxe5 27. Rd5 Qf6 (27... Qe6 28. Nf5
$14 {With annoying pressure for the pawn.}) 28. Ra1 g6 29. Ne4 Qc6 30. Nxc5
Rfe8 31. b4 $14 {with a light initiative. Anand,V (2768)-Mamedyarov,S (2801)
Saint Louis 2018 (В1/2-В1/2, 59)}) (24... Bxh4 25. Rxd2 Be7 26. Rd5 {Pawns are
equal but White has a dominating position. Black has to play the next move or
else die suffocating.} f6 27. e6 (27. exf6 Rxf6 $17 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd6b7,
Gb7a5]}) 27... f5 28. Qd3 (28. Qe1 Rf6 $17) 28... Qxe6 29. Nxf5 {Pawns are
again equal and White's domination is less stable. Black needs to make a few
more careful moves to equalize. Which he did not manage in the two games that
reached this position, Bruzon Batista,L (2689)-Mikhalevski,V (2552) Arlington
2013 (1-0, 60) and Caruana,F (2767)-L'Ami,E (2611) Reykjavik 2012 (1-0, 58).})
25. Ne4 (25. h5 Qe6 $1 {Black has to keep his queen central.} (25... Qxh5 $2
26. Re4 Qxd1+ 27. Rxd1 Bg5 28. f4 $16) 26. Ne4 (26. gxf4 Qg4+ {leads to a
perpetual.}) 26... Bxe5 27. Nxc5 (27. Qxd2 c4 28. bxc4 Qxc4 $11) 27... Qf5 28.
b4 Rad8 29. Ra1 {Otherwise the pawn on d2 is taboo.} Bf4 {The simplest.} (29...
Rfe8 {is a more complicated way to reach a perpetual.} 30. Rxd2 Bxg3 31. fxg3
Qg5 32. Ne4 Qe3+ 33. Kf1 Rxd2 34. Nxd2 Qd3+) 30. gxf4 Qg4+ {with a draw by
perpetual.}) 25... f5 26. Nxd2 (26. exf6 Rae8 27. fxg7 Rf7 $17 {offers Black
too much pressure.}) 26... Rad8 27. Ra1 {Removing the rook from the exposed
square.} (27. Qc2 Bxd2 28. Rxd2 Rxd2 29. Qxd2 f4 $11) 27... Rfe8 28. Qe1 Rd5 $1
$146 ({This is a more clear-cut path to a probable draw than} 28... Bxd2 29.
Rxd2 Rxd2 30. Qxd2 Rxe5 31. Qd8+ Re8 32. Qd5+ Qe6 33. Rd1 {But despite White's
activity and engines' optimism from White's point of view, Black could have
drawn at leisure in Caruana,F (2827)-Mamedyarov,S (2820) Batumi 2018 (1-0, 64)}
Qxd5 34. Rxd5 Re2 35. Rxc5 Rxb2 $11) 29. e6 (29. Nf3 {allows Black to force a
draw by perpetual.} Rd3 30. Nh2 Bxg3 31. fxg3 Rxg3+ 32. Kf2 Rg2+ 33. Kf3 Qc6+
34. Kf4 Qh6+) 29... Bxd2 30. Rxd2 Rxd2 31. Qxd2 Qxe6 $11 {This is a more
active version of that from the game above, with an obvious draw (even for
engines).} *

