1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. cxd4 {This exchange usually leads to
a queenless middlegame. Play is by far more interesting than in line 1, but
somewhat clearer than in Lines 2 to 4, where the minor details are very deep.
It is a face to face fight in a non-symmetrical position, offering both sides
chances.} Nxd4 13. Nxd4 ({It goes without saying that} 13. Be4 {does not make
any sense. But since it was played in a couple of games, here is just an
illustrative line.} Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxf3+ $5 $146 {How could one refrain from
this?} 15. Qxf3 O-O 16. Rd1 Qc8 17. h3 Bf5 18. Nc3 c6 $1 {Now that the knight
cannot get to d6, this is good and useful, as it prevents Nd5. Black has
comfortable play on the light squares.}) 13... Qxd4 14. Nf3 {White should
continue his development the fastest way possible.} (14. Qe2 Rd8 (14... O-O-O
15. Re1 Rhe8 {is also interesting.}) 15. Nf3 Qc4 16. Qxc4 Bxc4 17. Re1 Bd3 18.
Bd1 {In Richards,J (2072)-Ulker,A (2329) ICCF corr 2002 (0-1, 36) Black
embarked on some unclear adventures, but the simplest way to consolidate his
advantage was} Ne6 $15 {After installing the perfect blocking knight on e6 and
castling soon, he will be ready to advance his mobile majority.}) (14. Qf3 Bd5
$5 $146 {This natural move is as good as it looks. The bishop takes the longer
diagonal under control, making long castling even more viable, and clears the
e6 square for the knight.} 15. Qg3 (15. Qe2 O-O-O 16. Rd1 f6 17. Nf3 Qg4) 15...
h5 $15 16. Qxg7 $6 O-O-O {with a strong attack.}) 14... Qxd1 15. Rxd1 {Black's
active minor pieces compensate for White's space advantage. The e6-square is,
as usual, of crucial importance.} Rd8 {This is a simple way to get adequate
play. It reminds me of the Berlin Defence where the black king also navigates
along the back rank.} (15... Bg4 $2 {, heading for the regrouping with ...Ne6,
is simply bad:} 16. h3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 {The f-pawn(s) is(are) threatening.} g5
18. f4 $16 {Onischuk,A (2610)-Tong,Y (2505) Beijing 1998 CBM 066 [Mikhalevski,
V] (1-0, 30)}) ({The more complicated} 15... O-O {is analyzed in Lines 6 to 9.}
) 16. Rxd8+ (16. Nd4 {allows the similar regrouping with that failing above:}
Bg4 17. f3 Ne6 $1 18. Nxb5 (18. Nb3 Rxd1+ 19. Bxd1 Bf5 $11 {White will not
find it easy putting his kingside majority into motion as Black is better
developed..}) 18... Rxd1+ 19. Bxd1 axb5 20. fxg4 Bc5+ 21. Kf1 Ke7 $11 {White
has won a pawn and has two bishops. But his pawns are not very mobile and
Black is by far better developed.} 22. a4 (22. Bd2 Bd4 23. Bc3 Bxc3 24. bxc3
Ra8 $11) 22... Rd8 23. Be2 bxa4 24. Rxa4 Bd4 25. g3 Bxe5 26. g5 Nd4 {With such
a centralized knight Black cannot be in danger despite the two bishops.} 27.
Bc4 Nc6 28. Ke2 Rb8 29. b3 Nd4+ 30. Ke3 f6 {В1/2-В1/2 Fuhrwerk,K (2317) -Van
Wieringen,C (2304) ICCF email 2006}) (16. Be3 {runs into a typical counterplay.
} Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Na4 (17... Bxa2 $2 18. Bxc5 Bxc5 19. b3 {traps the bishop.
But after the last move both pawns are attacked for real.}) 18. Bxa4 (18. Bc1
Bxa2 19. b3 Nc3 20. Rd2 Bb1 $15) 18... bxa4 19. Nd4 (19. a3 O-O 20. Nd4 Bd7 $11
{[%cal Gf8b8]}) 19... Bxa2 20. Nc6 f6 21. Rc1 fxe5 22. Nxe7 Kxe7 23. Rxc7+ Kf6
{В1/2-В1/2 Laiz Ibanez,H (2274)-Santos Ruiz,M (2567) Linares 2019}) 16... Kxd8
17. Nd4 {Fighting against the blockade. White can also play this one move
later:} (17. Be3 Kc8 18. Nd4 (18. Ng5 Bd5 $5 19. Nxh7 Na4 20. b3 Nc3 {offers
Black excellent compensation for the pawn as White is busy defending his
queenside.} 21. Ng5 f6 22. exf6 Bxf6 23. Kh1 c5 24. a3 Kd7 $44 {White's extra
pawn does not make itself felt while Black's majority is threatening.}) 18...
Bd5 19. Nf5 (19. Rd1 {is parried with} c6) 19... Bf8 {White's success is only
temporary. He will be pushed back soon, while Black will keep the blockade on
the light squares and the queenside pressure.} 20. Rd1 c6 21. a3 g6 22. Ng3 (
22. Nh6 Be7 $11) 22... Be7 23. f4 Rd8 24. b4 Na4 25. Bxa4 bxa4 26. Bc5 {
In Hebels,A (2409)-Delavekouras,S (2406) ICCF email 2014 (В1/2-В1/2, 39) Black
just exchanged bishops, but he could have been more ambitious.} Bb3 27. Rxd8+
Bxd8 28. Ne4 Kd7 29. Kf2 a5 30. bxa5 Bxa5 $15 31. Nf6+ $6 Ke6 32. Nxh7 $6 Kd5
$17) 17... Bd5 18. Nf5 (18. Be3 Kc8 {transposes above.}) 18... g6 19. Nxe7 Kxe7
{Once again we have a position with a knight and a bishop against two white
bishops. Pawns are equal and the superior mobility of Black's majority
maintains equality.} 20. Be3 (20. Bg5+ Ke6 21. f4 Be4 $11) 20... Na4 21. b3 (
21. Bxa4 bxa4 22. a3 {В1/2-В1/2 Isolfsson,E (2446)-Walter,G (2452) ICCF email
2016}) 21... Nc3 22. f3 Ke6 23. Kf2 Rd8 24. Bd2 {Steiger,W (2427)-Walter,G 
(2452) ICCF email 2016 (В1/2-В1/2, 24)} b4 {Consolidating the knight is the
simplest.} 25. Bxc3 (25. a3 Bc6 26. Be1 Bb5 27. axb4 Nd5 $11 {Black retrieves
the pawn on e5 and has excellent minor piece outposts.}) 25... bxc3 $11 {
The pawn on c3 is vulnerable but White cannot defend e5 with} 26. f4 $2 {due to
} Bxg2 $1 $17 *

