1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Nf3 Qxd1
15. Rxd1 O-O {In the previous line the black king was headed for the kingside
or else e7. Castling is the fastest way to complete development but later the
king may need some time to return to the centre. All in all, after the last
move play tends to be more complicated than in Line 5, with increased chances
to outplay the opponent (but also to be outplayed!) Before proceeding I should
mention that this position has enjoyed intense practical rehearse. Both sides
have many alternatives on every step. I have tried to explain the main ideas
in the comments to this mass of practical material.} 16. Bg5 {From a classical
point of view, developing the bishop is the highest priority.} (16. Be3 {
is the other way of doing it.} Rfd8 17. Rdc1 $5 {White keeps all rooks on the
board, hoping to put pressure on Black' queenside.} (17. Nd4 Bd5 {transposes
to Line 8.}) 17... h6 {Avoiding problems along the c-file after Bg5.} 18. Nd4 (
18. Bxc5 Bxc5 19. Be4 {fails to win material:} Bd5 20. Rxc5 Bxe4 21. Rxc7 Bxf3
22. gxf3 Rd2 23. b3 Re8 24. Re1 Rxa2 25. f4 Rd2 26. Kg2 Rd4 27. Kf3 Rb4 28. Re3
g5 $11 {Saric,I (2626)-Nielsen,P (2670) Aix les Bains 2011 (В1/2-В1/2, 55)})
18... Bd5 19. f4 {The most ambitious continuation, planning f5. Pure piece
play does not bother Black:} (19. Bd1 Nd3 20. Rxc7 Bf8 21. e6 fxe6 22. Bg4 Re8
23. b3 Bd6 24. Rc2 Ne5 $11 {Hou,Y (2673)-Muzychuk,M (2554) Lvov 2016 CBM 172 
[Besenthal,K] (В1/2-В1/2, 81)}) (19. Nf5 Bf8 20. Bxc5 Bxc5 21. Bd1 Bf8 22. Rxc7
Be6 23. Ne3 Rd2 24. Bc2 Rad8 25. h4 Re2 26. b3 Ba3 27. Rb1 Rdd2 28. Rf1 Rd8 $44
{Robson,R (2465)-Kaidanov,G (2595) Saint Louis 2009 (В1/2-В1/2, 37)}) 19... Ne6
{Once again Black could have ignored the threat f4-f5.} (19... Bf8 $5 20. f5 $6
Re8 21. Bf4 Nd7 22. Re1 Bc5 23. Rad1 Rad8 $15 {With strong pressure against
White's over-extended position.}) 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. Bg6 Rac8 22. Bc5 Kf8 {
White's position looks a bit more pleasant but the possibility to active the
king more quickly allows Black to completely equalize.} 23. Kf2 (23. Bxe7+ Kxe7
{only helps Black, of course.} 24. Rc5 Bc4 25. b3 Bd3 26. Bxd3 Rxd3 27. Rac1
Kd7 28. Rc6 Rd4 29. g3 {В1/2-В1/2 (49) Hou,Y (2606)-Koneru,H (2610) Beijing 
(rapid) 2012} a5 30. Ra6 a4 {[%cal Gg7g5]}) 23... Bb7 $5 {[%cal Gd8d2]
Threatening ...Rd2+. White has problems maintaining the blockade.} 24. Bxe7+ (
24. Ke3 Bxg2) (24. Be3 c5) 24... Kxe7 25. Rc2 c5 26. Ke3 c4 27. a4 {So,W (2775)
-Ding,L (2778) Shanghai 2016 (В1/2-В1/2, 54)} Rd5 28. axb5 (28. Be4 Rd7 29.
axb5 Bxe4 30. Kxe4 axb5 31. Ra5 Rc5 $11) 28... Rxb5 $1 29. Ra3 a5 {With
entirely adequate counterplay.}) 16... Bxg5 17. Nxg5 h6 18. Nxe6 (18. Bh7+ {
forces the king farther from the centre but also implies moving with the
bishop again.} Kh8 19. Nxe6 Nxe6 20. Be4 Rad8 21. g3 Rfe8 (21... c5 $11) 22.
Bc6 (22. f4 g5 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. f5 Nd4 $11) 22... Re7 23. a4 Nd4 24. axb5 axb5
25. Bxb5 Nf3+ 26. Kg2 Rb8 27. Be2 {Svidler,P (2727)-Kramnik,V (2770) Dortmund
2004 (В1/2-В1/2, 27)} Nxe5 28. Rd2 g5 $11) 18... Nxe6 19. g3 Rad8 20. Kg2 g5 {
As so many other times, Black's majority is more mobile and the knight stands
well on e6, neutralizing the supposed bishop's superiority.} 21. Rac1 Rfe8 22.
b4 {Efimenko,Z (2636)-Lodici,L (2407) Antalya 2017 (1-0, 52)} Kf8 {[%cal Gc7c5]
Preparing ...c7-c5 by bringing the king closer to the centre.} (22... c5 {
is entirely possible, too.}) 23. Bb3 Nd4 24. Rxc7 Nxb3 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. axb3
Rd4 27. Rc6 Kg7 28. Rxa6 Rxb4 $11 *

