1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Nf3 Qxd1
15. Rxd1 O-O 16. Ng5 {This is quite active but practically forces White to
exchange on e6, which helps Black's regrouping.} h6 (16... Rfd8 {is
paradoxically also playable, as it causes White some back rank problems.} 17.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. Bxh7+ {Sreeves,C (2173) -Orsi,M (2037) Otranto 2011 (1-0, 44)} (
18. Nxh7 $2 Bf5 $1 {loses material.}) 18... Kf8 19. Nxe6+ (19. Bc2 $2 Bf5) (19.
Be3 Bxa2 $15 {Once again, Black's majority is more dangerous than White's.})
19... Nxe6 20. Bc2 Nd4 21. Bd1 Nc6 22. Be2 Nxe5 {Black has retrieved the pawn
and maintains excellent control in the centre.} 23. b3 Nc6 24. Be3 Nd4 25. Bd1
c5 26. a4 g6 27. axb5 axb5 $11) 17. Bh7+ {The same as in Line 5, White has a
choice between this intermediate move and the immediate exchange on e6, with
the aforementioned plusses and minuses.} (17. Nxe6 Nxe6 18. Be3 Bg5 19. Bxg5
hxg5 {reaches the same structure as in the mainline.} 20. Be4 Rad8 21. f3 c5
22. Kf2 c4 23. Ke3 (23. Rd6 Nc5 24. Rad1 {Giesen,K-Armani,G (1844) ICCF email
2016 (В1/2-В1/2, 25) The simplest way to neutralize White's structure and
maintain the more flexible pawns was:} Nxe4+ 25. fxe4 Rde8 26. R1d5 Re6 27. Ke3
Rc8 {followed by ...c4-c3, possibly after ...b5-b4.}) 23... Rc8 24. g3 {
1/2-1/2 (24) Dufour,M (2300)-Adams,M (2271) ICCF email 2016}) 17... Kh8 18.
Nxe6 Nxe6 19. Be4 Rad8 20. Be3 Bg5 {From a static point of view this is the
best way to consolidate the blockade.} (20... Bc5 {is entirely playable,
though, with similar play as in Line 5.} 21. Bxc5 Nxc5 22. Bd5 Na4 23. Bb3 {
Nyysti,S (2363) -Norri,J (2356) Finland 2008 (В1/2-В1/2, 56)} g5 $11) 21. Bxg5
hxg5 {Black has stabilized the knight without weakening the square on f5.
Double pawns can be strong sometimes, indeed.} 22. Kf1 {White's "working
agenda" is quite big. He has to centralize the king, try to put the pawns into
motion, set up pressure on the c-file. All these explain the alternatives to
the last move:} (22. g3 Rfe8 23. Bc6 Re7 24. Rd5 Rxd5 25. Bxd5 Nd4 26. Rd1 (26.
Re1 c6 27. Bg2 c5 28. Kf1 Kg8 $15 {leaves White short of active plans, while
the black king is ready to advance to b6.}) 26... c5 27. Kg2 (27. f4 $2 gxf4
28. gxf4 Ne2+ 29. Kf2 Nxf4 $17) 27... Rxe5 28. Bxf7 a5 {After the recent
structural modifications Black maintains his centralization.} 29. a4 b4 30. Kf1
g4 31. Re1 Nf3 32. Rxe5 Nxe5 33. Bd5 Kh7 34. Ke2 Kg6 35. Ke3 Kf5 36. b3 {
Timofeev,A (2658)-Movsesian,S (2642) Sarajevo 2007 (В1/2-В1/2, 40) If anything,
Black is not worse for sure.}) (22. Rac1 c5 23. Bb7 a5 24. Bd5 c4 25. Bxe6 {
White has to force the events towards a draw.} (25. g3 Nc5 $17 {followed by ...
Nd3.}) 25... Rxd1+ 26. Rxd1 fxe6 27. Rd6 Rc8 28. Kf1 b4 29. Ke2 c3 30. bxc3
Rxc3 31. Rxe6 Kg8 32. Rd6 Ra3 33. Rd2 {Tanti,J (2182)-Sigfusson,S (2242) ICCF
email 2014 (В1/2-В1/2, 33)} Kf7 $11) 22... g6 {The most harmonious pawns'
display, allowing ...Kg7 and anticipating g2-g3 followed by f2-f4, when
White's pawns would still not be threatening.} 23. Ke2 (23. Rac1 {does not
bring anything essentially new:} Kg7 24. Bb7 (24. g3 {Anand,V (2769)-Greenfeld,
A (2563) Haifa 2000 (В1/2-В1/2, 54)} c5 $11) 24... a5 25. Bc6 Nd4 26. Be4 Rfe8
27. Rc5 g4 28. h3 {A typical correspondence move, which would hardly cross an
over the board player's mind. After getting the f4-square for the knight Black
can never be worse.} (28. Rxc7 Rxe5 29. f3 a4 $11) 28... Rh8 (28... gxh3 29.
gxh3 c6 $11) 29. Rxc7 gxh3 30. gxh3 Rxh3 31. Rc5 Rh4 32. Bg2 Rdh8 33. Rd2 R8h5
34. Rd3 a4 35. Rd5 Ne6 36. Rxb5 Rc4 {Black's activity and knight's superiority
(already!) over the bishop offer him excellent compensation.} 37. Rc3 Rd4 38.
Rd5 Rb4 39. b3 axb3 40. axb3 Nf4 41. Rdc5 Rd4 $44 {Polubabin,V-Szerlak,A (2309)
ICCF email 2017 (В1/2-В1/2, 48)}) 23... Kg7 24. g3 (24. Ke3 c5) 24... Rfe8 25.
Ke3 Rxd1 {Black chooses the safest plan, simplifying to a draw.} (25... g4 $11)
(25... c5 $11) 26. Rxd1 Nc5 27. f4 gxf4+ 28. Kxf4 (28. gxf4 $2 {weakens the
pawns on h2 and f4.} Rh8 29. Rd2 Rh3+ 30. Bf3 Ne6 $17) 28... Ne6+ 29. Ke3 Rh8 (
29... Nc5 $5 30. Rd5 (30. Kf4 Ne6+ $11) 30... Na4 31. b3 Nc3 32. Rc5 Nxa2 33.
Rxc7 Rxe5 34. Kd4 Re6 35. Bd5 Rf6) 30. h4 Rh5 31. Rd5 c6 32. Rd6 Rxe5 33. Kf3
c5 34. Rxa6 Nd4+ 35. Kf4 f6 36. Ra7+ Kh6 37. g4 Ne6+ 38. Kf3 Nd4+ {В1/2-В1/2
Efimenko,Z (2703)-Caruana,F (2712) Poikovsky 2011} *

