1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Nf3 Qxd1
15. Rxd1 O-O 16. Nd4 {This is more flexible than 16.Ng5. True, White does not
attack h7, but his knight maintains a choice for the future. It can jump to c6,
f5 or take on e6 at the right moment.} Rfd8 17. Be3 (17. Nxe6 {is premature
and likely to cause a delay in development.} Rxd1+ 18. Bxd1 fxe6 ({There is
nothing wrong with the familiar} 18... Nxe6 {, but the game move keeps the
knight closer to d3.}) 19. Bc2 Rd8 20. Kf1 Nd3 21. f4 c5 22. Ke2 c4 $11 {
Senders,M (2061)-Lacrosse,M (2203) Vlissingen 2013 (В1/2-В1/2, 33)}) (17. Nc6 {
yields White only a temporary initiative.} Rxd1+ 18. Bxd1 Bf8 19. Bf3 Re8 20.
Be3 {Isgandarova,K (2193) -Cornette,D (2392) Mamaia 2016 (0-1, 60). There are
several good moves now, but the most clear-cut way of neutralizing White's
pressure is} Bd7 21. Rd1 Bxc6 22. Bxc6 Re6 23. Bf3 Rxe5 24. Rd8 Ne6 25. Ra8 g6
26. Kf1 Kg7 27. Rxa6 Bc5 28. Bd2 Nd4 {Even though White has the two bishops,
with such a centralization Black does not risk anything.} 29. Bd1 Rd5 30. Be1
h5 $11) (17. b4 Na4 {renews the choice for White.} 18. Nc6 (18. Nxe6 {is bad
with the pawn hanging on b4.} fxe6 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. a3 c5 $15) 18... Rxd1+
19. Bxd1 Bf8 20. Bf3 Re8 21. a3 Nb6 22. g3 h6 23. h4 g6 24. Bg2 Bg7 (24... Bd5
{looks more principled to me, as it yields Black the control over the light
squares.} 25. Bxd5 Nxd5 26. Bf4 Nb6 27. Rc1 Nc4 28. a4 g5 $5 {The simplest way
to an obvious draw, but not forced at all.} 29. hxg5 hxg5 30. Bxg5 Nxe5 31.
axb5 axb5 32. Nxe5 Rxe5 $11) 25. f4 f6 26. Bb2 fxe5 27. Bxe5 Nc4 28. Bxg7 Kxg7
29. a4 bxa4 30. Rxa4 Bg4 $11 {Black has enough counterplay to compensate for
the queenside weaknesses, Hou,Y (2578) -Koneru,H (2600) Tirana 2011 (В1/2-В1/2,
43)}) 17... Bd5 18. Rdc1 $5 {An original idea (even though we have seen
something similar before). White avoids the rooks' exchange, sets up pressure
on the c-file and keeps a2 defended.} (18. f4 {displays White's cards a bit
prematurely, helping Black to formulate his plan.} g6 19. Rac1 Ne6 20. Ne2 (20.
f5 {only weakens White's position.} Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Bg5 22. Ra1 gxf5 23. Bxf5
Bxa2 $1 24. Rxa2 Rxd4 $17) 20... b4 $1 {The best plan. Black restricts the
enemy knight. The weakness on c4 is irrelevant as the knight cannot reach this
square. Besides, most natural alternatives have drawbacks.} (20... Kg7 {
exposes the king to} 21. f5 gxf5 22. Ng3 {with some initiative.}) (20... a5 {
weakens b5.} 21. Rxd5 Rxd5 22. Be4 Rad8 23. Bxd5 Rxd5 24. Nc3 Rd3 25. Kf2 $14)
21. Rxd5 (21. f5 {just loses a pawn.} gxf5 22. Bxf5 Bxa2 $15 {, and b2-b3 is
not available.}) (21. b3 {offers Black a clear target.} a5 22. f5 gxf5 23. Bxf5
a4 $15) 21... Rxd5 22. Be4 Rad8 23. Bxd5 Rxd5 24. Rc6 a5 {As usual, the strong
knight on e6 offers Black excellent play despite his backward pawn on c7.} 25.
Kf2 (25. g4 g5 $11 26. f5 Rxe5 27. Kf2 Bc5) 25... Bc5 (25... h5 $11) 26. g3 h5
27. Bxc5 Nxc5 28. Rxc7 Nd3+ 29. Ke3 Nxb2 $11 {Rhodes,J (2399)-Kerr,S (2460)
ICCF email 2016 (В1/2-В1/2, 36)}) (18. b3 {is over cautious.} g6 19. f3 Ne6 20.
Kf2 {В1/2-В1/2 Zupe,M (2336)-Stamnov, A (2184) Skopje 2012} Nxd4 21. Bxd4 c5
22. Be3 Rac8 23. f4 Be6 {Black's position is preferable due to his mobile
pawns.}) (18. h4 {is quite abstract but basically slow.} Ne6 (18... Bxh4 $2 19.
Nf5 $18) (18... Na4 $5) 19. Nf5 Bf8 20. f3 (20. f4 {looks more logical, but
Black can hold his own.} a5 21. Ng3 Nc5 22. f5 c6 {The pawn on e5 is likely to
become a liability soon.}) 20... a5 21. Ng3 a4 22. Be4 c6 23. f4 g6 $11 24.
Bxd5 $2 {A huge mistake, increasing the e6-knight's strength.} cxd5 25. f5 {
1/2-1/2 (41) Lopez Martinez,J (2545) -Delorme,A (2483) Barcelona 2015} d4 $1
26. Bf2 gxf5 27. Nxf5 d3 $17) (18. Nf5 {[%emt 0:00:09] is examined in Line 9.})
(18. Rac1 {[%emt 0:00:10] is examined in Line 10.}) 18... Ne6 $146 {Keeping
things simple.} (18... g6 19. f4 f6 {also looks fine.}) (18... Bf8 {is in
principle good, but offers White a free tempo on a plate and thus requires
certain accuracy later.} 19. Ne2 Ne6 (19... c6 $5 {, consolidating Black's
centre, may be an improvement. And if} 20. f4 Ne4 $11 {[%cal Gf7f6] , followed
by ...f7-f6.}) 20. f4 c5 21. f5 Nd4 (21... Nc7 $5 22. Nf4 Re8) 22. Nxd4 cxd4
23. Bxd4 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Rxd4 25. Bb3 Rf4 (25... Rd2+ $1 {Black should have kept
his counterplay going with} 26. Kf3 Rad8) 26. Rc7 Rxf5 27. Rf1 Rxf1 28. Kxf1
Kh8 29. Bxf7 $14 {1-0 (59) Leko,P (2744)-Johannessen,L (2519) Tromsoe 2013})
19. Nf5 (19. Ne2 {leads to similar play as in the game above, but with an
extra tempo for Black:} c5 20. f4 g6 $15) 19... Bf8 20. f4 Rd7 $11 21. Ng3 c5
