1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Nf3 Qxd1
15. Rxd1 O-O 16. Nd4 Rfd8 17. Be3 Bd5 18. Nf5 {In this concrete position, the
familiar knight jump is usually connected with some active and concrete idea.}
Bf8 19. Bg5 (19. Nd6 {is best met with} Bxg2 20. Bxc5 {Most consistent.} (20.
Nxf7 {leads to a draw by force.} Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Bf3 22. Rd4 {The only move,
defending the knight indirectly in view of Rf4+.} Ne6 23. Bb3 Nxd4 24. Nh6+ Kh8
25. Nf7+ Kg8 26. Nh6+ Kh8 27. Nf7+ {В1/2-В1/2 Gharamian,T (2649)-Wagner,D 
(2569) Biel 2015}) (20. Kxg2 {loses a pawn with just reasonable compensation
due to the two bishops.} cxd6 21. exd6 Rxd6 22. Rxd6 Bxd6 23. Rd1 Bf8 24. b4
Ne6 {Black is well regrouped and cannot be worse.}) 20... cxd6 21. exd6 Bf3 22.
Rd2 {White has created a far-advanced passed pawn, but Black can surround it
and neutralize its strength.} g6 23. a4 Rac8 24. b4 Bh6 25. Rd3 Bc6 26. axb5
Bxb5 27. Rdd1 Bf8 28. Ba4 Bxa4 29. Rxa4 Rc6 30. Ra3 f6 31. Kg2 Kf7 $11 {
Volokitin,A (2672)-Sutovsky,E (2654) Poikovsky 2008 (В1/2-В1/2, 37)}) (19. Rd2
{plans to double rooks along the d-file, but this is not dangerous.} Ne6 20. a3
(20. Ng3 {Kurgansky,V (2391)-Cumming,D (2244) ICCF email 2014 (В1/2-В1/2, 52)}
Bb4 {As an over-the-board player I find this most logical, causing White to
abandon his initial plan.} 21. Rdd1 Bc5 22. Bxc5 Nxc5 23. f4 (23. b4 Ne6 {
followed by ...a6-a5.}) 23... a5 24. Nf5 Kf8 25. Rd2 Bc4 26. Nd4 a4 $11) 20...
Bb7 ({Actually this is not really necessary.} 20... a5 21. Rad1 c6 $11 {If} 22.
Bb6 Rdb8 {only wastes time for White.}) 21. Rad1 Rxd2 22. Rxd2 a5 23. Bb3 b4
24. axb4 axb4 25. f3 Ra5 26. f4 g6 27. Ng3 Bc5 $11 {The bishop o b7 is very
strong, compensating for White's advantage in the centre. Nijboer,F (2540)
-Ernst,S (2589) Haaksbergen 2009 (В1/2-В1/2, 32)}) 19... Rd7 20. Ne7+ (20. Ne3
{is too passive.} Be6 21. Rxd7 Nxd7 22. Be4 Rb8 23. Bf4 Nc5 24. Bc2 Rd8 $17 {
Kalinina, M (2047)-Golub,D (2277) Kishinev 2013 (0-1, 63)}) 20... Bxe7 21. Bxe7
Ne6 {The knight is very strong now, but White still has some hopes due to the
pin along the d-file.} 22. Be4 c6 23. Bxd5 (23. Bh4 Re8 $11) 23... Rxd5 24.
Rxd5 cxd5 25. Rc1 {White seems to be active, but this game once again proves
the knight's strength.} h5 {Black does not wish to weaken f6 until he forces
the bishop to step back.} ({But the other possible way to activate the king,} 
25... g5 {, is also playable:} 26. g4 Kg7 27. Kg2 h5 28. Kg3 Re8 29. Bf6+ Kg6
30. h4 ({Or if} 30. Rc6 h4+ 31. Kg2 a5 32. a3 a4 33. Rb6 Rc8 34. Rxb5 Rc1 $11 {
[%cal Gd5d4] followed by ...d5-d4 with excellent counterplay for the pawn.})
30... gxh4+ 31. Kxh4 Rg8 $5 32. b3 {There is little more that White can do.} (
32. Rc6 $2 {misplaces the rook.} hxg4 33. Kxg4 Kh6+ $17 34. Kf5 $2 Nd4+) (32.
gxh5+ $2 Kf5 {puts the enemy king in irremediable trouble.}) 32... Kh6 33. gxh5
Nf4 $11) 26. f3 Kh7 27. Kf2 Nf4 28. Rd1 {Hard to understand why White gave up
the c-file.} ({But} 28. Rc2 d4 {is also pleasant for Black.}) 28... Rc8 29. Rd2
d4 30. g4 $2 {Another mysterious move, weakening White's structure.} (30. g3
Ne6 31. f4 Kg6 32. Kf3 Rc1 33. h3 {offers White all the chances to survive.})
30... Ne6 31. h4 Rc7 32. Bb4 g5 $17 {After clearing the path for his king,
Black has excellent winning chances, Svidler,P (2739)-Caruana,F (2670)
Amsterdam 2009 (0-1, 43)} *

