1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Nf3 Qxd1
15. Rxd1 O-O 16. Nd4 Rfd8 17. Be3 Bd5 18. Rac1 {Abstractly, the most logical
move. Before undertaking anything concrete, White completes his development.}
Ne6 19. Nf5 Bf8 20. a3 {A favourite plan of Vachier-Lagrave, which does not
seem to pose Black too many problems. In fact, the move is easy to understand
as the pawn on a2 is hanging for good, as the following line shows.} (20. Ng3
Bxa2 $5 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. b3 a5 23. Ra1 Bxb3 $1 24. Bxb3 a4 25. Bc2 {В1/2-В1/2
(42) Domancich,E (2415)-Kerr,S (2466) ICCF email 2015 Black's pawns are
dangerous, but Black has to bring in all the available resources.} Bc5 26. Bxc5
Nxc5 27. Nf5 Kf8 28. Ne3 b4 29. Bxa4 {A desperate attempt to reach equality.} (
{The king's centralization mainly wastes time.} 29. Kf1 a3 30. Ke2 Ne6 $17 {
followed by ...c7-c5.}) 29... Ra8 30. Nc2 Rxa4 31. Rxa4 Nxa4 32. Nxb4 Ke7 $15 {
Due to the passed c-pawn and the more active king, Black retains the better
chances in the knight ending.}) (20. Bb1 {also looks logical, as it clears the
c-file. But the bishop is not especially active on b1.} Rac8 {My favourite
move, completing development and preparing the advance of the c-pawn.} (20...
Bb7 21. f4 g6 22. Ng3 Bh6 23. Rf1 c5 24. Ne4 {yielded White some initiative,
but Black managed to neutralize it.} Bxe4 25. Bxe4 Rac8 26. g3 Bf8 {with
satisfactory play for Black, Azarov,S (2585)-Robson,R (2667) chess.com INT
2019 (В1/2-В1/2, 30)}) (20... c5 $6 {is prematurely weakening d6.} 21. f4 g6
22. Nd6 Bxd6 23. Rxd5 $14) 21. f4 (21. Nd6 cxd6 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 23. Rxd5 dxe5 24.
Rxe5 Rd8 25. Bc2 g6 26. Re4 Bg7 {The rook is awkwardly placed on e4 and White
has to weaken his queenside. Black will play ...Nd4 soon, with complete
equality.}) 21... g6 22. Ng3 Bh6 23. Rf1 Bc4 24. Rf2 Bd3 {A coherent plan to
invade the light squares.} 25. Ne4 Bxb1 26. Rxb1 Rd3 27. Re1 Rcd8 28. g3 Bf8
29. Rc2 c5 30. b3 {Both sides have deployed their forces optimally. Black
needs to take a concrete decision, as after centralizing the king, White could
hope to capitalize on his space advantage.} Nd4 $1 (30... Kg7 31. Kf2 Nd4 {
, as in Prince,B (2279)-Rueda Marquez,D (2066) Barcelona 2016 (1-0, 49), White
could have avoided the exchange with} 32. Rcc1 $14) 31. Bxd4 R3xd4 $11 32. Nxc5
Rd2 33. Rxd2 Bxc5+ 34. Rf2 Rd2 35. Ref1 Rxa2 36. b4 $1 {Forced as otherwise
the pawn ending would be bad for White.} Bxf2+ 37. Rxf2 Ra4 38. Rb2 h5 $11)
20... b4 ({The most active answer, even though the solid} 20... Rd7 {is also
OK:} 21. Nd6 c6 22. Ne4 Rad8 23. f4 c5 24. f5 Nd4 25. Nxc5 Bxc5 26. Bxd4 Bf3 $1
{Forcing a draw.} 27. Bxc5 Rxd1+ 28. Bxd1 Rxd1+ 29. Rxd1 Bxd1 {and the second
half of Vachier-Lagrave,M (2723)-Wei,Y (2721) Leon (rapid) 2015 (В1/2-В1/2, 66)
was obviously completely unnecessary.}) 21. axb4 (21. a4 Rab8 {[%cal Gb4b3,
Gb8b4]} 22. b3 $6 {[%csl Gb3]} g6 $36) 21... Bxb4 22. Nd4 a5 23. f4 g6 ({
Actually it was not necessary to take measures against f4-f5 yet:} 23... a4 24.
f5 Nxd4 25. Bxd4 a3 26. bxa3 Bxa3 27. Ra1 g6 28. g4 Bf3 29. Rd3 Be4 30. Raxa3
Rxa3 31. Rxa3 Bxc2 $11) 24. f5 Nxd4 25. Bxd4 Bf3 $1 {A familiar drawing
combination.} 26. gxf3 Rxd4 27. Be4 Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Re8 29. f4 gxf5 30. Bxf5 f6
31. Bd7 Rf8 32. Be6+ (32. e6 Rb8 33. b3 Bd6 34. Rd3 Kf8 $1 {Preparing ...Rb4
in view of White's resource Rxd6!} 35. Rh3 Kg7 36. Rg3+ Kf8 $11) 32... Kh8 33.
exf6 {В1/2-В1/2 Vachier Lagrave,M (2785)-Sethuraman,S (2639) Gibraltar 2016} *

