1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 {This is the classical mainline. Unlike 9.c3 it does not put
immediate pressure on Black, but it prevents him from breaking in the centre
at an early stage.} Bc5 {According to Tarrasch, this move is inferior as it
exposes the bishop. But I have always been fascinated by it, as it develops
most actively. In this line we will examine a series of sidelines that in some
cases require certain accuracy from Black.} (9... Be7 {is a more solid, but
also less ambitious alternative.}) ({Now is a good moment to explain in which
way 9.c3 prevents an early central break:} 9... Nc5 10. Bc2 Be7 11. Re1 (11.
Nbd2 d4 {would transpose to the previous lines with 9.Nbd2}) 11... O-O (11...
Bg4 {is the main continuation, transposing to 10...Bg4, which is a more common
move order. I used to play this line a lot, but as explained in the
introduction, I eventually had to admit that it presents Black with a lot of
problems.} 12. Nbd2) 12. Nd4 $14) 10. Bf4 {This seemingly active move, aiming
at consolidating e5, loses the pawn with just reasonable compensation.} (10.
Bc2 {does not have much of an independent value.} O-O 11. Bf4 $2 {This is much
worse than a move earlier.} (11. Qe2 {[%emt 0:00:12] transposes to Line 12.}) (
11. Nbd2 {transposes to the main lines with 10.Nbd2.}) 11... f6 $1 {Due to the
pressure on f2, White's position falls apart.} 12. Nbd2 Nxf2 $1 {A strongly
improved version of the Dillworth attack.} 13. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 fxe5 15. Bg3
e4 $19 {De Rijk,J-Picard,S ICCF corr 1997 (0-1, 27)}) (10. a4 {aims at
weakening the black queenside, but it achieves the opposite after} b4 {It is
only White who has queenside weaknesses now.} 11. a5 (11. Nd4 Nxe5 12. cxb4
Bxb4 {fails to shatter Black's stability.}) 11... O-O 12. Ba4 Ne7 ({There does
not seem to be anything wrong with} 12... Nxa5 $15 {, but the game move is
solid enough.}) 13. Nd4 Rb8 14. Be3 $2 {Asking for trouble.} (14. Bc2 {is
better. Black can continue with} Ng6 {, planning ...Qh4 with active
counterplay, as White is still underdeveloped. If} 15. f3 $2 bxc3 16. bxc3 $2
Rxb1 $1 17. Bxb1 Nxc3 18. Qd3 Bxd4+ 19. Qxd4 Ne2+ {wins}) (14. f3 $2 bxc3 $17
15. bxc3 $2 Rxb1 $19) 14... Nf5 15. Qf3 Bxd4 (15... bxc3 {also makes sense, as
it opens the b-file for the rook.} 16. bxc3 Bxd4 17. cxd4 Rb2 $17) 16. cxd4 f6
17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Bxd2 Nxd4 19. Qe3 {Polgar,J (2630)-Piket,J (2605) Monte Carlo
1994 (1-0, 28)} c5 $19) (10. Nd4 {gives up a pawn without offering attacking
chances.} Nxe5 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Qh5+ Ng6 13. Bc2 Nxf2 $1 14. Bxg6+ Kd7 15. Bf7
(15. Bc2 Rf8 16. Nd2 Ng4+ 17. Kh1 Rxf1+ 18. Nxf1 Qf6 $19) 15... Rf8 16. Rxf2
Bxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Qf6+ $17) ({For} 10. Qe2 {[%emt 0:00:12] see Line 12.}) ({For} 
10. Qd3 {[%emt 0:00:13] see line 13.}) (10. Nbd2 {[%emt 0:00:18] is examined
in lines 15 to 18.}) 10... g5 $1 {The most resolute answer.} 11. Bc1 {
Paradoxically, the only good move. White has spent two tempi on provoking
Black to weaken his kingside.} (11. Bg3 $2 h5 $19) (11. Be3 $6 Bxe3 12. fxe3 g4
13. Nd4 g3 $3 $146 {A fantastic attacking move, leaving the knight on c6
undefended.} 14. Nxe6 (14. Nxc6 gxh2+ 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Rg8 $19) (14. hxg3
Qg5 $17 15. Nxc6 Qxe3+ 16. Kh2 Qxg3+ 17. Kh1 Rg8 18. Qf3 Qh4+ 19. Kg1 Rg3 20.
Qe2 Kd7 $19 {, followed by ...Rag8.}) 14... gxh2+ 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 fxe6
$17) 11... g4 12. Nd4 Nxe5 13. a4 {Trying to weaken Black's queenside, too.} (
13. Nd2 Ng5 14. Re1 Qf6 $17 15. Nf1 $2 Bxd4 16. cxd4 Nh3+ 17. gxh3 Nf3+ 18. Kh1
Nxe1 19. Qxe1 Qf3+ 20. Kg1 gxh3 21. Ne3 Kd7 $19 {Plat,V (2410)-Simacek,P (2493)
Decin 2009 (0-1, 26)}) (13. Bf4 Qf6 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. a4 b4 $17 {Myers,
J-Stephson,D (2240) Queensland 1994 (0-1, 53)}) 13... Qf6 $146 {As in the
lines above, Black immediately uses the availability of this square after the
pawn on e5 has been eliminated.} 14. Nd2 (14. axb5 $2 Nf3+ $1 $19) 14... O-O
15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. axb5 axb5 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 {Black is a pawn up
while his structure is weak. But most importantly he is very active.} 19. Qe2
Qg6 20. Qxb5 Nf3+ 21. Kh1 Nxh2 {Leading to a forced draw.} 22. Qb7 {Removing
the queen from the exposed square.} (22. Kxh2 $2 g3+ 23. fxg3 Qh5+ 24. Kg1
Bxd4+ {wins the queen.}) 22... Rf8 23. Kxh2 Qh5+ 24. Kg1 g3 25. fxg3 Rxf1+ 26.
Kxf1 Qd1+ 27. Kf2 Qc2+ $1 {with a perpetual.} *

