1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Qe2 {This move is closely related to 10.Qd3 from Line 13, to
which it can actually transpose. There are two basic ideas behind it:
exchanging the active bishop with Be3 or else questioning the central knight's
stability.} O-O 11. Nbd2 (11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 f5 {transposes to Line 13.}) (
11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6 Qxf6 {offers Black active play.} 13. Be3 (13. Nbd2 Nxd2 14.
Bxd2 Bg4 15. Qd3 Bxf3 16. Qxh7+ Kf7 17. gxf3 Ne5 $15) (13. Bg5 $2 Nxg5 14. Nxg5
Qxg5 15. Qxe6+ Kh8 16. Na3 (16. Qxc6 Rxf2) 16... Rxf2 17. Rxf2 Rf8 18. Kh1 (18.
Raf1 Rxf2) 18... Rxf2 $19 {Golmayo de la Torriente,M-Steiner, L The Hague 1928
(0-1, 25)}) 13... Bg4 14. Qd3 Rad8 $15 {With an obvious advantage in
development for Black.} 15. Bxc5 $2 Bxf3 16. gxf3 (16. Bxf8 Ne5 17. Qe3 Qg6 18.
g3 Qg4 19. Nd2 Ng5) 16... Ne5) 11... Bf5 {Consolidating the outpost.} ({
Unlike in Line 13, Black is hanging along the e-file after} 11... f5 12. exf6)
12. Nxe4 {The way White has planned his development, there is no way back.} ({
True, he can insert} 12. a4 b4 {before} 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Ng5 Nxe5 15. Nxe4 {
The changed queenside structure induces some modifications in the mutual plans,
too.} Qd3 (15... Bg4 {is less effective now, as after} 16. Qd2 $1 {Black is
hanging on b4.}) 16. Qxd3 Nxd3 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 {Giving up the bishops' pair
makes sense as White's queenside squares are weak now.} 18. Bc4 (18. Bd1 bxc3
19. bxc3 Nd3 20. Be3 Rab8 $11 {Black's activity compensates for the two
bishops.}) 18... bxc3 19. bxc3 Bd3 20. Bxd3 Nxd3 21. Be3 Rfd8 $11 {Chances are
equal, but the position remains full of life due to the thematic fight between
the knight and the bishop. Theoretically, the latter is more mobile, but with
so many weak light squares the knight can jump around a lot.} 22. Rfb1 (22.
Rab1 {leaves a4 vulnerable.} Rab8 23. Rfd1 Rxb1 24. Rxb1 Nb2 {Black has the
initiative already.} 25. a5 Rd1+ 26. Rxd1 Nxd1 27. Bd4 Nb2 28. Bb6 $5 c6 {
Thanks but no thanks.} 29. Kf1 Kf8 30. Ke2 Ke7 31. Kd2 Kd6 32. Kc2 Nc4 $17)
22... Rab8 23. Kf1 {Geller,J (2549)-Druska,J (2385) Pardubice 2013 (В1/2-В1/2,
46)} Nb2 24. Bd4 f6 25. g4 Kf7 26. Ra2 Nc4 $11) (12. e6 $2 {is just a blow
into the wind, leaving White underdeveloped after} Nf6 13. exf7+ Rxf7 $17 {
Kalezic,B (2460)-Caruana,F (2646) Budva 2009 (0-1, 65)}) (12. Bc2 $2 {loses a
pawn to} Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bxc2 $17) 12... dxe4 13. Ng5 Nxe5 14. Nxe4 Bg4 {The
most active.} (14... Qd3 {may also be alright, but with the white queenside
compact, Black may be struggling a bit.} 15. Qxd3 Nxd3 16. Nxc5 Nxc5) 15. Qc2 (
15. Qd2 {does not make sense, now that there is no queenside tension.} Qxd2 16.
Bxd2 Bb6 17. a4 (17. Be3 {sadly for White, he has to play this sooner or later.
} Bxe3 18. fxe3 a5 $146 19. a4 Rab8) (17. Ng3 Nd3 18. Rab1 Rfe8 19. Bc2 Rad8
$17 {Yuvarajan,P (2189)-Mikhalevski,V (2551) Arlington 2013 (0-1, 62)}) 17...
Rfe8 $146 18. Be3 {What else? Black's pressure is too strong.} Bxe3 19. fxe3
Be2 20. Rf2 Bc4 $15) 15... Bb6 {The position is symmetrical and chances are
equal. But there is play left, of course.} ({Black could actually offer a move
repetition with} 15... Bf5 $11 {White is best adviced to accept it, as after}
16. Bf4 Re8 $15 {he gets under pressure.}) 16. Bf4 (16. Bg5 Qd3 17. Rfe1 Bf5
$15) 16... Nd3 17. Bg5 (17. Bd6 {more or less forces a draw.} Bf5 18. Qxd3 (18.
Bxf8 {exposes White to a strong attack:} Bxe4 19. Qe2 Qh4 20. g3 (20. Ba3 Nf4
$1 21. Qxe4 Nh3+ $1 $19) 20... Nf4 $1 21. gxf4 Qxf4 22. Bd1 {The best defence
against the threatened mate.} Rxf8 $15 {, with fantastic compensation for the
exchange.}) 18... Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Qxd6 $11) 17... Qd7 18. Kh1 (18. Rad1 $2 {
does not work due to the back rank weakness:} Bxd1 19. Rxd1 Rae8 20. Rxd3 Rxe4
$19) 18... c5 19. Be3 {White has to prevent ...c5-c4 at any cost.} Bf5 20. f3
Rab8 21. c4 Be6 22. cxb5 (22. Rfd1 bxc4 23. Bxc4 Bxc4 24. Qxc4 Nxb2 25. Rxd7
Nxc4 $11) 22... c4 23. Bxc4 Bxc4 24. Bxb6 Rxb6 25. Qxc4 Nxb2 26. Qc2 Rxb5 $11 *

