1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Qd3 {This move has a long history, althogh it never was the
mainline. In the '80s it served Andrei Sokolov quite well, including his
Candidates' match with Jussupov. As we will see, there are two possible plans
on the next move.} O-O {The other plan is} 11. Be3 {, starting the fight for
the dark squares. But moving twice with the queen while development is
incomplete restricts White's chances for an advantage.} (11. a4 {is premature,
allowing Black to take over the initiative on the kingside.} f6 $1 12. axb5 (
12. exf6 Qxf6 13. axb5 $2 Ne5 $1) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. Be3 Bxe3 15.
Qxe3 axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. f3 Nd6 18. Qxe5 Bf7 $15 {With space advantage and
better development.}) (11. Nbd2 {is examined in Line 14.}) 11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3
{Black has a free tempo to anticipate Nbd2.} f5 $1 {The best way to start
queenside counterplay.} (12... f6 {may transpose if White takes on f6, but he
can do better:} 13. Rd1 {Suddenly there are problems along the d-file. The
immediate threat is Qxe4.} Bf7 14. Nbd2 $14 {Fier,A (2566)-Vovk,A (2551)
Dieren 2011 (1-0, 55)}) 13. Nbd2 {White is heading for a heavy strategical
battle.} (13. exf6 {frees Black's play while also helping his development.}
Qxf6 14. Nbd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 (15. Nxd2 Bf7 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] leaves the queen
exposed to a rook on e8.}) 15... Rad8 16. Rfe1 Bg4 {Black is well developed
and has good counterplay.} 17. Re3 (17. Nd4 Na5 18. f3 Bc8 {[%cal Gc7c5]
followed by ...c7-c5.}) 17... Na5 18. Ne5 {Shmit,A-Solmanis, Z Riga 1963 (1-0,
41)} Bh5 19. f3 Nxb3 20. axb3 c5 $11 {The strong knight only compensates for
Black's mobile central majority.}) (13. Nd4 {is just clearing the path for
Black's f-pawn.} Nxd4 14. cxd4 f4 15. Qd3 f3 16. g3 Ng5 $17 {Adam, E-Watzl,L
ICCF corr 1950 (0-1, 22)}) 13... Qe8 $1 (13... Qe7 {may seem more natural, but
with the f3-square over-defended,} 14. Nd4 {may offer White a small plus. In
the mainline, the queen is on a better trajectory to anticipate this.}) 14.
Rad1 {A natural move, completing development.} (14. a4 {achieves little:} Rd8
15. axb5 axb5 $11) (14. Nd4 {allows the familiar counterplay:} Nxd4 15. cxd4 f4
16. Qe2 Nxd2 17. Qxd2 f3 18. g3 Qh5 $1 {The point behind 13...Qe8. Without
this quick queen transfer to the kingside Black would be simply worse.} 19. Kh1
Rf5 $3 {The correct move order.} (19... Qh3 $2 20. Rg1 Rf5 21. g4 $16) 20. a4 (
20. h4 Qg4 21. Kh2 Rh5 $19) 20... Qh3 21. Rg1 Qxh2+ $1) ({Since in the
mainline White gets under a pin along the d1-h5 diagonal, it is worth checking
what could happen if he refrains from Rad1:} 14. Rfe1 $146 Kh8 15. Bc2 Bg8 16.
Nb3 b4 17. Nbd4 bxc3 18. bxc3 (18. Ba4 cxb2 $1 {This would not be available
after Rad1.} 19. Rab1 f4 {Suddenly the queen does not have any good squares.
One way or another, White has to allow Black to free himself from the pin.} 20.
Qa3 Qe7 $1) 18... Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 20. f3 c5 21. fxe4 cxd4 22. cxd4 Qc7 23.
Rac1 fxe4 24. Bxe4 Qa5 $11) 14... Rd8 15. Rfe1 Kh8 16. Bc2 (16. Qf4 {exposes
the queen to} Ne7 17. Nd4 Bg8 18. Qe3 c5 19. Ne2 Ng6 20. f4 Qc6 $11 {Gralke,W 
(1801)-Puleston,T (1845) IECG email 2003 (В1/2-В1/2, 40) After putting his
pawns into motion, Black has a good position.}) 16... Bf7 $1 ({Better than} 
16... Bg8 17. Nb3 $14 {Pilnik,H-Sliwa,B Munich 1958 (0-1, 54), with good
control on the dark squares.}) 17. Nb3 Bh5 {The point.} 18. Nbd4 Nxe5 19. Nxe5
Bxd1 20. Bxd1 Qxe5 21. f3 Rd6 22. fxe4 dxe4 {A comfortable version of the
Dillworth attack. The material balance is about even and Black is quite active.
} *

