1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Qd3 O-O 11. Nbd2 {As far as development is concerned, the
most logical move. White immediately challenges Black in the centre.} f5 12.
exf6 {Andrei Sokolov's speciality.} (12. Bc2 $5 Qd7 13. Nb3 Be7 $1 {Keeping
the bishop safe from the exchange is a good positional idea.} 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15.
Nxd4 (15. cxd4 {Hard to say if this was a prepared novelty or simply
over-the-board inspiration in Anand,V (2794)-Sethuraman,S (2617) Douglas 2017 
(1-0, 51).} f4 {Since White is far from exerting pressure along the c-file,
this looks like the best plan.} 16. Bd2 {Black should have used his more
active position to start a positional attack with} g5 17. Ba5 g4 18. Nd2 Ng5
19. f3 c5 $15) 15... c5 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 {leads to the same type of position as
in the line played in Anand-So, published in this same article. White is a
tempo up (Qd3) but surprisingly this helps Black:} 17. f3 c4 $1 {A useful gain
of time, restricting the c2-bishop and clearing the c5-square his own.} 18. Qe2
Bc5+ 19. Be3 (19. Kh1 Ng3+ 20. hxg3 f4 21. Bxf4 Rxf4 22. Rf2 Rf7 $17) 19... f4
20. Bxc5 Nxc5 21. Rad1 Rad8 22. Qf2 Qc6 23. Rd2 Ne6 {With such a knight Black
has little to fear.} 24. Rfd1 g6 25. h4 Rf7 26. h5 {Aridov,V (2316)-Evchin,M 
(2270) Kiev 2017 (В1/2-В1/2, 51) Black should have kept the kingside blocked
with} g5 $1) 12... Nxf6 {Black is active and better developed, but he also
faces the risk of hanging a bit in the centre.} 13. a4 {This move is aimed at
inducing some improvements before switching to Ng5.} (13. Ng5 {is premature:}
Ne5 14. Qg3 (14. Nxe6 Nxd3 15. Nxd8 Raxd8 $17) (14. Qe2 Qd6 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16.
Ne4 Nc4 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $15) 14... Qd6 15. Ndf3 Nxf3+ 16. Nxf3 Rae8 (16... Qxg3
{is also playable, but I feel that it strengthens White's structure a bit.} 17.
hxg3 Ne4 18. Nd4 Bf7 19. Be3 Rfe8 20. Rfe1 {, with some light pressure Tilak,S
(2315)-Barua,D (2450) Kolhapur 1987 (0-1, 38).}) 17. Qxd6 ({White has to
exchange queens as after} 17. Nd4 Qd7 $15 {his queen would remain exposed.})
17... Bxd6 $11) 13... Bf7 {This subtle move not only threatens the brutal ...
Bg6, but also changes the dynamics of the position. The point is that if White
decides to exchange the bishop, ...Ne5xf7 would lead to a harmonious
regrouping.} (13... Rb8 {is likely to offer White some initiative:} 14. axb5
axb5 15. Ra6 Qd7 16. Ng5 {Now everything is prepared for this.} Ne5 17. Qe2 Bd6
18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. Ne4 Nc4 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. g3 Rbe8 22. Qd3 Qf7 23. Bc2 $14 {
Van Kampen,R (2580)-Mikhalevski,V (2551) Calgary 2013 (В1/2-В1/2, 57)}) 14. Ng5
({White does not have the time for} 14. axb5 {, as} Bg6 15. Qe2 Re8 16. Qd1
axb5 $15 {would leave him underdeveloped.}) 14... Ne5 15. Qg3 Qe7 $1 $146 {
AT this stage it is better to keep the queens on the board.} (15... Qd6 16.
Nxf7 Nxf7 17. Nf3 Qxg3 18. hxg3 {Sokolov,A (2635)-Jussupow,A (2635) Tilburg
1987 (В1/2-В1/2, 64)} Nd6 $5 $11) 16. Nxf7 (16. Bc2 Bg6 17. Bxg6 Nxg6 $15 {
also offers Black some kingside initiative.}) 16... Rxf7 $15 {Black is better
developed and White has to be careful already. Once again, he does not have
the time for:} 17. axb5 $2 Nh5 18. Qh3 Nf4 {, trapping the queen.} *

