1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2 {The most natural plan, putting pressure on e4 with
developing moves.} O-O 11. Bc2 (11. Nxe4 {can only cause problems to White.}
dxe4 12. Ng5 (12. Bxe6 {just opens the f-file for Black's attack.} Qxd1 13.
Rxd1 fxe6 14. Nd4 Nxe5 $17 {Black has won a pawn and has good control on the
light squares and better development.}) 12... Bxb3 13. axb3 (13. Qh5 {starts
an adventure in which White can hope for a draw by perpetual in the best case.}
h6 14. Nxe4 Bc4 15. Bxh6 {Otherwise just loses material.} Be7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17.
Qg4+ Kh6 18. Qh3+ Bh4 19. Rad1 Qe7 20. Nf6 Nxe5 {White's compensation for the
sacrificed material remains unclear.}) (13. Qxb3 e3 $19) 13... e3 14. Bxe3 (14.
Qxd8 $2 exf2+ $19 {Filipi,S (2255)-Simacek,P (2454) Pardubice 2015 (0-1, 32)})
14... Bxe3 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. fxe3 Nxe5 {With a pleasant ending for Black.}) (
11. Qe2 {transposes to Line 12.}) 11... Nxf2 $5 {This is the start of the
so-called Dilworth attack. Vernon Dilworth used it a couple of times in the
'40s, but there had been just one previous game with this line in 1924! At the
top level, Botvinnik played it in 1943 against Smyslov, but chose the wrong
move order and lost. As a general picture, Black gets a rook and a pawn for
two minor pieces and, based on his better development, a consistent initiative.
This most typically results in winning a second pawn, after which he will have
nothing to fear, even in the endgame. The remarkable thing is that the old
theory is still valid in the essential lines, standing up to the engines'
scrutiny.} 12. Rxf2 f6 $1 {The key to the sacrifice. Black opens the f-file
for his attack.} 13. Nf1 {This move has enjoyed some popularity lately. White
immediately sacrifices a pawn to speed up his development. But Black's strong
centre yields him entirely adequate play.} (13. Nb3 $2 {is weaker, as it
leaves the kingside poorly defended.} Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 fxe5 15. Kg1 Bg4 16. h3
Bh5 17. g4 e4 18. Nh2 Qh4 19. Qxd5+ Bf7 20. Qxc6 Qf2+ 21. Kh1 Qxc2 $19) (13.
exf6 {[%emt 0:00:17] is examined below in Lines 16 and 17.}) 13... Bxf2+ (13...
fxe5 $2 14. Be3) 14. Kxf2 fxe5 15. Kg1 Qd6 {The most natural developing move.}
16. Ng3 (16. Ng5 {does not achieve much.} Bf5 17. Bxf5 (17. Bb3 $6 {fails to
cause problems in the centre and actually allows Black to gain time to put his
pawns in motion:} Ne7 18. Ne3 Rad8 $1 19. Bd2 c5 $17 {Darga,K-Larsen,B
Copenhagen 1953 (1-0, 49)}) 17... Rxf5 18. Qd3 e4 19. Qh3 Qg6 20. Ng3 Rf6 {
With his pieces massed in a narrow space and facing the threat ...h7-h6, White
does not have anything better than offering a draw by repetition with} 21. Nh5
Rf5 22. Ng3 {, which Black can decline if he wishes, with approximately equal
chances.}) (16. a4 {should be met with natural moves:} h6 (16... b4 {
indirectly weakens d5.} 17. Be3 bxc3 18. bxc3 Ne7 $2 {Zamora,S (1840)-Pecotic,
K (1894) IECG email 2004 (0-1, 29)} 19. c4 $1 $14) 17. Be3 Rad8 18. Qe1 Bf5 $11
) (16. Be3 {is an untested but natural developing move.} h6 17. Qe1 (17. b4 {
runs into} d4 18. cxd4 exd4 19. Nxd4 Nxb4 20. Nxe6 Nxc2 21. Qxc2 Qxe6 $15 {
The centre has opened in Black's favour.}) 17... e4 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Rf6
20. Ng3 Raf8 $11 {With no pawn breaks in view, White's stability is enough for
just static equality.}) 16... Bg4 $1 {A strong attacking move, after which
tactics work out well for Black.} (16... h6 17. Qe1 $6 {White continues to
neglect his development.} (17. Be3 $5) 17... e4 $1 (17... Bg4 18. Nh4 $1 {
with unclear play in Vachier Lagrave,M (2779)-Mamedyarov,S (2801) Biel 2018 
(В1/2-В1/2, 42).}) 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. cxd4 c5 $1 20. Be3 c4 $1 $15 {with an
improved version of the structure reached after the above 16.Be3.}) 17. h3 (17.
Bxh7+ $2 Kh8 $1 18. Bc2 $2 Qc5+ 19. Kh1 Qf2 $1 $19) 17... Bxf3 18. gxf3 Ne7 (
18... e4 19. f4 {is not entirely clear.}) 19. Qd3 Ng6 $17 {Black has the
better structure and attacking chances.} *

