1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2 12. Rxf2 f6 13. exf6 {The main
continuation, of course.} Bxf2+ $1 {Black should not delay this anymore.} ({If
} 13... Qxf6 $2 14. Qf1 $16 {, as in the aforementioned Smyslov,V-Botvinnik,M
Moscow 1943 (1-0, 50).} ({As a historical curiosity, the first recorded game
with the Dilworth attack went} 14. Nb3 $6 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Ne5 {transposing
below, Rey Ardid,R-Kleczynski,J Paris 1924 (1-0, 24).})) 14. Kxf2 Qxf6 15. Kg1
{Unpinning the knight in anticipation of ...Ne5.} (15. Nb3 {aims at keeping
the blockade in the centre, but in the ensuing ending the white king will be
too exposed to allow White hoping for more than a draw.} Ne5 16. Kg1 (16. Nbd4
$2 {allows Black creating a lethal tension:} Bg4 {Threatening ...c7-c5.} 17. b4
$5 Qb6 $1 $146 {The best move, putting White under some deadly pins. There
simply is no way out:} 18. Bb3 c6 19. Kg3 Qc7 20. Kf2 Nxf3 21. Nxf3 Bxf3 22.
gxf3 Qxh2+ {with a winning attack.}) (16. Nc5 {only increases Black's advance
in development after} Rae8 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 $17) 16... Rae8 17. Be3 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3
Qxf3 19. gxf3 Rxf3 20. Bc5 Bh3 21. Nd4 Rf6 {Things look great for White in the
centre, but on the kingside he is vulnerable.} 22. Kh1 $1 {The only defence,
preparing Rg1.} (22. Bb3 $2 Re5 $19 {Pollack,O (2150)-Mirzoyan,D (2382) London
2018 (0-1, 35)}) 22... Re5 23. Rg1 Rf2 24. b4 h5 $5 {The position may still be
equal, but only Black can play for a win.}) (15. Nf1 {is examined in Line 17.})
15... Rae8 $1 {Black simply completes his development, taking advantage of the
fact that with his knight on d2 yet, White cannot do the same yet.} (15... Ne5
$2 {is premature due to} 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Nf3 Qh5 18. Qd4 $16 {, when White
is in complete control.}) 16. Nf1 (16. Qf1 Bf5 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 18. b3 (18. a4
bxa4 19. Rxa4 {В1/2- (24) В1/2 Macovei,A (2352)-Morozov,N (2437) Anogia 2017}
Qc2) 18... d4 19. cxd4 Nxd4 20. Ba3 (20. Nxd4 $2 Qc5 21. Bb2 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 Re2
23. Rf2 Rxf2 24. Kxf2 Qd5 25. Ke3 Qe5+ {0-1 (25) Ljubojevic,L (2625)-Jussupow,
A (2635) Tilburg 1987}) 20... Ne2+ 21. Kh1 c5) (16. h3 {Still preparing Nf1.}
Bxh3 $3 $146 {A brilliant novelty, forcing White to find a safe way to
equality. White should not have feared ghosts.} 17. gxh3 {leads to the usual
equal ending:} (17. Nf1 $2 Ne5 $17 {1-0 (29) Amonatov,F (2610) -Hansen,S (2595)
Baku 2016 CBM 175 [Marin]}) 17... Ne5 18. a4 (18. Kg2 Ng6 19. Bxg6 Qxg6+ 20.
Kf2 Qb6+ 21. Kf1 $6 Re6 $40) (18. Nxe5 $2 Qf2+ 19. Kh1 Rxe5 $19) 18... Nxf3+
19. Nxf3 Qxf3 20. Qxf3 Rxf3 21. axb5 axb5 22. Kg2 Rf6 (22... Rxc3 23. Bxh7+
Kxh7 24. bxc3 Re2+ 25. Kg3 Rc2 {is also interesting.}) 23. Bd3 Re1 24. Ra8+ Rf8
25. Rxf8+ Kxf8 26. Bf4 c6 27. Kf3 g6 {with a probable draw.}) ({A neutral move
such as} 16. a4 {allows Black to display the hidden idea of his last rook move.
} Ne5 17. axb5 axb5 $15 18. Nxe5 $2 Qf2+ 19. Kh1 Bh3 $1 20. gxh3 Rxe5 $19)
16... Ne5 17. Be3 {White is best adviced to keep developing.} (17. Nxe5 $2 Qf2+
{mates}) 17... Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 Qxf3 19. gxf3 Rxf3 {This is a typical Dilworth
ending. From a material point of view, Black is doing at least fine and he is
quite active, too. The only thing he has to care about is to keep White from
becoming active, because then his bishops could become dangerous. At the
moment, Black's queenside lacks mobility, but his main plan is based on ...
g7-g6 followed by ...h5-h4, restricting the enemy knight.} 20. Bf2 {The safest
move, controlling e1.} (20. Bd4 Bh3 21. Ng3 g6 {does not change anything to
White's favour.} 22. a4 Kf7 23. axb5 axb5 24. Rd1 h5 {, with a black
initiative, Savon,V (2455)-Serper,G (2485) Moscow 1990 (В1/2-В1/2, 32)}) 20...
Bh3 21. Ng3 (21. Nd2 Rf6 (21... Rf4 22. Bg3 Rg4 23. Kf2 Rf8+ 24. Ke3 Re8+ 25.
Kf2 Rf8+ 26. Ke3 {1/2-1/2 (53) Ismagambetov,A (2525)-Filippov,A (2584)
Tashkent 2009}) 22. Re1 Rxe1+ 23. Bxe1 Re6 24. Kf2 Bg4 25. Bd3 c5 26. Bf1 c4
27. Bg2 Rd6 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 28. Ke3 Re6+ 29. Kf2 Rd6 30. Ke3 Re6+ 31. Kf2 {
В1/2-В1/2 Perez Candelario,M (2524)-Kolev,A (2571) Navalmoral 2010}) 21... g6
22. Re1 (22. Rd1 c6 23. Rd2 Rf4 24. Bd3 (24. Bd1 h5) 24... a5 25. Bf1 Bxf1 26.
Kxf1 a4) (22. a4 c6 23. axb5 axb5 24. Rd1 Re5 25. Rd2 h5) 22... Rxe1+ 23. Bxe1
c5 (23... h5 24. Bd1 Rf7 25. Bf2 h4 26. Nf1 c6 27. Nd2 g5 $11 {Aseev,K (2440)
-Agzamov,G (2545) Sevastopol 1986 (В1/2-В1/2, 39)}) 24. Bf2 c4 25. a4 bxa4 26.
Bxa4 Rf8 27. b4 cxb3 28. Bxb3 Be6 29. Ne4 a5 30. Nc5 Kf7 31. Bd4 Ke7 32. Kg2 g5
33. Bc2 Bf5 34. Bb3 Be6 35. Bc2 {Black now even avoided a draw by repetition
with} h6 $11 {, but chances are about even anyway, as White is very solid.
Aseev, K (2565)-Mikhalevski,V (2545) Beersheba 1998 (В1/2-В1/2, 51)} *

