1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2 12. Rxf2 f6 13. exf6 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2
Qxf6 15. Nf1 {The most consistent continuation. White prepares to develop and
keeps f3 over-protected.} Ne5 16. Be3 (16. Kg1 {leads to similar play as in
Line 16.} Nxf3+ (16... Rae8 {leads to an exact transposition to Line 16, but
Black can think of later playing ...Raf8 insted of ...Re8.}) 17. Qxf3 Qxf3 18.
gxf3 Rxf3) 16... Rae8 17. Bc5 (17. Bd4 {is best met with} Qh4+ (17... Bg4 18.
N1d2 {offers White some chances to consolidate.}) 18. Kg1 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Bh3
20. Ng3 {Nukin,A (2338)-Bezgodov,A (2503) Izhevsk 2011 (В1/2-В1/2, 34)} (20.
Bf2 Qh5 {wins the pawn on f3, with similar play as in Line 16.}) 20... Qf4 $5
$146 {The only way to defend f3 is} 21. Bf2 c6 22. Qd3 g6 23. Bd1 {, but this
does not neutralize Black's initiative.} Re6 24. a4 {What else?} h5 25. axb5
axb5 26. Qd4 Qxd4 $5 {This leads to a very instructive ending.} (26... Qg5 {
is also possible.}) 27. cxd4 Rfe8 {At this moment, White is almost in Zugzwang
and has to choose each move with care.} 28. Rb1 (28. Nf1 $2 Re1 $19) (28. Rc1
h4 {29.Nf1 Re1 loses, leaving White with nothing better than} 29. Ne4 dxe4 30.
Bb3 $15) (28. Kh1 $2 Re1+ $19) (28. Bb3 {is safe, but Black can force a move
repetition with} Rf8 29. Bd1 {if he wishes so.}) 28... h4 29. Nf1 g5 ({With
the rook on b1} 29... Re1 $2 30. Bxe1 Rxe1 {runs into} 31. Bc2) 30. Nd2 {
The only way to display any activity. The knight is heading for c5.} (30. Ra1
Re1 $1) 30... Ra8 31. Nb3 (31. Nf1 $11 {is safer}) 31... Bf5 32. Ra1 {Again
the safest.} (32. Rc1 Ra2 33. Nc5 Rf6 $1 {Defending the bishop in order to
prevent White from freeing himself with Bc2.} 34. b3 Rf7 $1 {Again close to
Zugzwang.} 35. b4 Rg7 {The Zugzwang is more clear now, but the threat ...g5-g4
is in the air, too.} 36. Be3 Re7 37. Bf2 Rf7 38. Be3 Bh3 $19) 32... Rxa1 33.
Nxa1 Bd3 34. Nb3 Be2 35. Nc5 Re7 36. Bxe2 Rxe2 37. b3 h3 $11 {Black is very
active but has no way to break through.}) (17. Kg1 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 Qxf3 19. gxf3
Rxf3 {is an exact transposition to Line 16.}) 17... Nxf3 18. gxf3 Rf7 19. Kg2 (
{If} 19. Kg1 {, the simplest is} Bf5 (19... Qxf3 20. Qxf3 Rxf3 21. Re1 {
[%cal Gf1d2,Gd2b3] pins the bishop and prepares Nd2-b3-d4 with certain
pressure.}) 20. Bxf5 Qxf5 21. Kg2 Qg5+ 22. Ng3 h5 $1 23. f4 $1 Qxf4 24. Qxh5
Qd2+ 25. Kh1 Qxb2 26. Rg1 {White has just enough play to force Black to give a
perpetual.} Qxc3 27. Nf5 Re6 28. Bd4 Qc2 29. Bxg7 Qe4+ 30. Rg2 Qe1+ 31. Rg1 $11
) (19. Ng3 Bg4 {leads to a familiar ending.} 20. Kg1 Qxf3 21. Qxf3 Rxf3 22. Kg2
h5 23. Bg6 $6 (23. Rf1 $11) 23... Re6 24. Bxh5 Rxg3+ 25. Kxg3 Bxh5 $15 {
Leko,P (2555) -Jussupow,A (2655) Horgen 1994 (В1/2-В1/2, 51).}) 19... Qg5+ 20.
Ng3 (20. Kh1 {allows the same pawn break:} d4 $1 {Clearing the d5-square for
the bishop.} 21. Bxd4 (21. Qxd4 Rxf3 22. Be4 Rf4 $19) 21... Bd5 22. Bb3 (22.
Nd2 Rxf3 $1 23. Nxf3 Re1+ $1) 22... c5 23. Be3 (23. Bxd5 Qxd5 24. Bf2 Qxf3+ 25.
Qxf3 Rxf3 26. Bxc5 Re2 27. Rb1 h5 28. Ng3 Rc2 $11 {Black's activity
compensates for the material disadvantage.}) 23... Bxb3 24. Bxg5 Bxd1 25. Rxd1
Rxf3 26. Kg2 Rf5 27. h4 Re2+ 28. Kg3 $1 (28. Kh3 Rxb2 29. Ne3 Rff2 $1 $17 {
Acs,P (2460) -Mikhalevski,A (2470) Budapest 1997 (0-1, 47).}) 28... Rxb2 29.
Ne3 $1 {This is the point! With the king on h3 the knight's advance would not
be possible.} Rf7 30. Rd8+ Rf8 31. Rd7 $11) 20... d4 $1 {The same idea as
above.} 21. Bxd4 (21. cxd4 Bd5 22. Bb3 Re3 $19) 21... c5 22. Bf2 Rxf3 $1 23.
Be4 {White is defending with the only moves.} (23. Kxf3 Bg4+ $17) (23. Qxf3 Bd5
$17 24. Be4 $2 Bxe4 $19) 23... Bh3+ $1 (23... Rf6 {is also playable, retaining
reasonable compensation.}) 24. Kxh3 (24. Kg1 $2 Rxg3+ 25. hxg3 Rxe4 $17) 24...
Rxf2 25. Qd5+ Qxd5 26. Bxd5+ Kh8 $11 {White has managed to parry the attack,
but his king is misplaced and Black retains his activity. A possible
continuation is} 27. b3 (27. b4 Rd2 28. Bb7 cxb4 29. cxb4 Rb8 30. Be4 g6 $11)
27... Re3 28. a4 Rd2 $1 29. c4 b4 30. Rf1 h5 {At this point White has to find
a way to a draw.} 31. Rf8+ Kh7 32. Be4+ g6 33. Rf6 Rd4 34. Kg2 $1 (34. Bxg6+
Kg7 35. Rxa6 h4 $19) 34... Rexe4 35. Nxe4 Rxe4 36. Rxa6 $11 *

