1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3 {The setup introduced by this move has been considered as important
as 9.c3 for many decades.} ({True, the traditional move order used to be} 9. c3
Be7 10. Be3 {, but when 9...Bc5 became popular, White started playing 9.Be3.})
9... Be7 ({One important discovery, making 9.Be3 popular at the beginning of
the late '80s, was that} 9... Nc5 {runs into} 10. Nc3 $1 Nxb3 11. cxb3 $1 Be7
12. Rc1 {, leaving Black with problems on the dark squares and along the
c-file.}) 10. c3 ({The move order} 10. Nbd2 O-O {mainly transposes after 11.c3,
as} 11. Nxe4 {does not promise much:} dxe4 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Nd2 Nxe5 14. Nxe4
$11 {В1/2-В1/2 Kobalia,M (2614)-Golod,V (2582) Biel 2005 does not offer White
anything.}) 10... O-O 11. Nbd2 Qd7 {A logical setup, developing naturally
without being worried about the central tension.} 12. Nxe4 (12. Nd4 {is a not
entirely sound pawn sacrifice:} Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Nxe5 14. f4 Nc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16.
f5 Bd5 17. Rad1 Be4 18. Bh6 $6 {Thematical but wrong.} gxh6 ({Black could even
ignore the bishop with} 18... c5 19. Bxg7 cxd4 20. f6 Rfe8 21. fxe7 Kxg7 $19)
19. Qxh6 Kh8 20. Rde1 Bd5 21. f6 Rg8 22. Rf5 Bf8 23. Qh4 Rxg2+ 24. Kf1 Rg6 $19
{Bosiocic,M (2607)-Ivanchuk,V (2727) Mali Losinj 2017 (0-1, 28)}) (12. h3 {
loks like an attempt to prevent ...Bg4, which is an important issue in Line 19.
} Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Na5 {A similar reaction as in Line 20.} 14. Rad1 Rad8 (14...
Nxb3 15. axb3 a5 $11) 15. Bc2 Nc4 16. Qd3 (16. Qc1 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 c5 18. Ng5
Bxg5 19. Qxg5 {1/2-1/2 (47) Kevlishvili,R (2451)-Matlakov,M (2700) St
Petersburg 2018} f6 $11) 16... g6 17. Bc1 Bf5 ({Unlike in the similar position
reached in Line 20,} 17... f6 18. exf6 Bxf6 {allows} 19. Nd4 $14 {under
favourable circumstances, as White's rooks are connected already.}) 18. Qe2
Bxc2 19. Qxc2 f6 20. exf6 Bxf6) (12. Bc2 {[%emt 0:00:19] is examined in Line
19.}) ({and} 12. Re1 {in Line 20.}) 12... dxe4 13. Qxd7 (13. Bxe6 Qxe6 14. Nd4
{Nunn,J (2584)-Holzke,F (2468) Germany 2002 (В1/2-В1/2, 29)} Nxd4 15. cxd4 f5
16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Qc2 c6 18. Rac1 Rac8 19. Rfe1 Rfd8 $11) 13... Bxd7 14. e6 {
The critical move, weakening Black's structure. Otherwise, the pawn exchange
in the centre would lead to obvious equality.} (14. Nd2 Nxe5 15. Nxe4 Bc6 16.
Bc5 (16. Ng3 {Rosen,L-Lasker,E Paris 1900 (0-1, 56)} g6 $11) 16... Rfe8 17.
Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Nc5 Nd7 $11 {В1/2-В1/2 O'Kelly de Galway,A-Unzicker,W Varna 1962}
) (14. Rfd1 {is an attempt to improve over the previous line.} Rad8 15. Ng5
Nxe5 16. Nxe4 Bc6 17. Bc5 {The difference is that the pawn on a6 is undefended
now. In Aravindh,C (2543)-Harsha,B (2344) Noida 2016 (В1/2-В1/2, 68) The most
convincing reaction was} Bxc5 18. Nxc5 a5 19. a4 bxa4 20. Bxa4 Bxa4 21. Nxa4
Nd3 22. Rd2 Rd6 $11 {With the knight arrested on a4, White cannot really enjoy
his structure.}) 14... Bxe6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Nd2 Ne5 17. Nxe4 Nc4 18. Bc1 Rf5
{Black's better development and the weakness on d3 compensate for the minor
structural defect.} 19. b3 (19. a4 {Asrian,K (2645) -Ivanchuk,V (2748)
Stepanakert 2005 (В1/2-В1/2, 20)} a5 $5 20. axb5 Rxb5 21. Ra2 Kf7 $11 {The
pressure along the b-file and his superior activity offer Black good play,
despite his isolated pawns all over the board.}) (19. Re1 Rd8 20. b3 Nd6 21.
Nxd6 Bxd6 {This ending is similar to the one arising in Line 1.} 22. Be3 Kf7
23. a4 Bc5 24. g4 Re5 25. Bxc5 Rxc5 26. axb5 axb5 27. Re3 h5 28. h3 {В1/2-В1/2
Erenburg,S (2573)-Fressinet,L (2625) Reykjavik 2006}) 19... Nd6 20. Ng3 Rd5 21.
Be3 Bf6 22. Rac1 Kf7 23. Rc2 Rd8 {Black is perfectly regrouped and his chances
are not worse.} 24. Re1 (24. c4 bxc4 25. bxc4 Ra5 $15) 24... Rd3 25. Bd4 Rd7
26. f3 {In order to stay in the game, White has to sacrifice the pawn.} (26.
Ne2 $2 Nf5 27. Bxf6 gxf6 $17 {Thipsay,P (2475)-Sasikiran,K (2514) Guntur 2000 
(0-1, 62)}) 26... a5 $5 (26... Bxd4+ 27. cxd4 Rxd4 28. Ne2 Rb4 29. g3 {Offers
White certain compensation, as the rook is passive on b4.}) 27. Ne4 Nxe4 28.
Rxe4 Bxd4+ 29. cxd4 $11 R3xd4 {Not necessary, but good enough.} 30. Rxd4 Rxd4
31. Rxc7+ Kf6 $11 {With an obvious draw.} *

