1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Qd7 12. Bc2 {The most straightforward
continuation, forcing Black to take a decision regarding his central knight.}
Nxd2 ({The old mainline went:} 12... f5 13. exf6 Nxf6 {A recent game continued
with} 14. Bg5 $5 Bd6 15. a4 b4 16. a5 bxc3 17. bxc3 Qf7 18. Re1 h6 19. Bh4 Ng4
(19... Nh5 $11 {is safer.}) 20. Bg3 Bxg3 21. hxg3 Bf5 22. Ba4 Nxa5 {1/2-1/2 
(31) Polgar,J (2710)-Koneru,H (2589) Caleta 2012} 23. Nd4 Bc8 (23... Bc2 24.
Qxg4 $18) 24. N2f3 c5 25. Bc2 Nc4 26. Nc6 Be6 27. Qd3 Nf6 28. g4 $5 {With some
light initiative.}) 13. Qxd2 Bg4 (13... Na5 {is less appropriate with the
bishop on c2 already:} 14. Nd4 c5 15. Qd3 g6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bh6 Rf7 18. Qg3
Kh8 19. h4 $36 {Giri,A (2791)-Pruijssers,R (2507) Amsterdam 2015 (1-0, 43)})
14. Qd3 {The only way to keep the pawn on e5 and avoid doubled kingside pawns.}
(14. Bf4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 {has been played a few times.} Nd8 $1 {Planning to set
up the blockade with ...f7-f5 and ...Ne6.} (15... Rad8 {It surely takes some
effort to criticize this natural move that completes Black's development. But
the Open Spanish has its own rules, due to the non-symmetrical structure.
After the light-squared bishop has disappeared, Black needs to block the
e6-square with her knight, and the last move delays it indefinitely. I
remember how surprised I was when this move was played in Hou, Y (2673)
-Muzychuk,M (2554) Lvov 2016 (1-0, 32), which I was watching live. Strangely,
it was played in all the few modern games with this line.}) 16. Bg3 (16. Rad1
c6 17. Bg3 (17. Kh1 $6 {was played in Nyman,S-Lilloni,L Italy 1972 (В1/2-В1/2,
47). It is refreshing to see that in those years one would understand that 15..
.Nd8 is THE move.} Qh3 18. Bg3 Ne6 19. f4 f5 20. exf6 Bxf6 $15) 17... f5 $1 18.
exf6 {This offers Black excellent play, but otherwise White would find it
difficult to generate any active plan after ...Ne6.} Bxf6 19. Qd3 g6 20. f4 Bg7
{White does not have full compensation for the shattered structure.}) 16... c6
$1 {Still preparing ...f7-f5.} (16... f5 $6 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Qf4 c6 19. Qg4 {
with the initiative.}) 17. f4 f5 18. exf6 {Otherwise ...Ne6 would reach an
optimal blockade, leaving both white bishops passive.} Bxf6 {followed by the
knight transfer to d6.}) 14... g6 15. Bh6 (15. Bf4 {allows a similar plan as
in the main game:} Bf5 16. Qe2 Bxc2 17. Qxc2 Nd8 18. Rad1 Ne6 19. Bh6 Rfd8 20.
h3 c5 21. Rd2 Qc6 22. Rfd1 Rd7 $11 {Kholmov,R (2505) -Kots,Y Saratov 1981 (1-0,
48)}) 15... Rfe8 16. Rfe1 {Just one of the possible centralizing moves.} (16.
Rad1 {as in Bodnaruk,A (2475)-Buksa,N (2288) Mamaia 2016 (0-1, 45), requires a
change of the initial plan due to the pressure on d5:} Bf8 $1 {Black
immediately attacks e5.} 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. Rfe1 Re7 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 Rae8
$11) (16. Rae1 {is less natural than the main game move and should be met in
the same way:} Bf5 17. Qd2 {Klinger,J (2460)-Unzicker,W (2470) Graz 1984 (В1/
2-В1/2, 59)} Bxc2 18. Qxc2 Nd8 $11) 16... Bf5 $1 ({With the e5-pawn defended,} 
16... Bf8 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 {as in Hakobyan,A (2466)-Torosyan,N (2350) Yerevan
2017 (В1/2-В1/2, 92), works out less well:} 18. h3 $1 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 $14 {
The e5-pawn is not edible because of Qf6.}) 17. Qd2 Bxc2 18. Qxc2 Nd8 $1 19.
Rad1 Ne6 $11 {Black has exchanged all unnecessary minor pieces and occupied
the perfect e6-square with his knight. The position is objectively equal, but
I would always prefer playing with Black here.} 20. h4 (20. Re3 Rad8 21. h4 {
inhibits ...c7-c5 but places the rook on a vulnerable path:} Qc6 22. Red3 Qb7
23. Qd2 c6 24. Bg5 Nc5 25. Rd4 Ne4 26. Qf4 {Kabisch,T (2246)-Amos, F (2094)
Gruenbach 2014 (1-0, 48)} Qc7 $1 $11 {[%csl Ge5]}) 20... c5 {Black's pawns are
ready to advance while White's kingside attacking chances are less clear.} 21.
h5 Rad8 22. a4 {Possibly underestimating the next move.} (22. Rd3 c4 23. Rd2 b4
$132) 22... bxa4 $1 {White needs to worry about his b2-pawn now.} 23. Ra1 Rb8
24. Bc1 (24. Rxa4 Rxb2 $1) 24... Rb6 25. Rd1 {Apparently, one warning was not
enough. White should not have left his other rook pawn en prise for too long.}
(25. hxg6 hxg6 26. Qxa4 Qxa4 27. Rxa4 Rd8 $11) 25... Rd8 26. Rxa4 gxh5 $1 $15 {
A pawn is a pawn, and the g-file is useful for Black's attack. Kokarev,D (2638)
-Short,N (2664) Kolkata 2015 (0-1, 47).} *

