14. Nd4 (14. Bg5 Bg4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. a4 d4 $15 {David,A (2580)-Vocaturo,D 
(2588) Milan 2015 (В1/2-В1/2, 32)}) 14... Nxd4 15. cxd4 c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 {
Black is well developed, so his central pawn is more of a strength than a
weakness.} 17. Rc1 Rc8 18. h3 d4 19. Qf3 d3 20. Red1 Bd4 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Bxe6
Qxe6 23. b3 Qxe5 24. Qxd3 Qf6 25. Be3 Bxe3 26. Qxe3 h6 $11 {Adams,M (2742)
-Muzychuk,M (2528) Baku 2015 (В1/2-В1/2, 41)}) 13... Na5 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4]} 14.
Bc2 (14. Bg5 Nc4 15. Bxc4 bxc4 $11 {Kotronias,V (2620) -Sokolov,I (2685)
Monaco 2006 EXT 2015 [RR] (В1/2-В1/2, 24)}) (14. Nd4 Nc4 15. Bxc4 bxc4 $11) (
14. Rad1 Nxb3 15. axb3 Rfd8 16. h3 a5 17. b4 axb4 18. cxb4 Ra4 19. Bc5 Bxc5 20.
bxc5 d4 21. b4 Bb3 22. Rb1 Bc4 $11) 14... Nc4 15. Qd3 g6 16. Bc1 (16. Bh6 {
does not offer White sufficient compensation for the pawn.} Nxb2 17. Qd4 Rfe8
18. Ng5 Nc4 $15 {Gligoric,S-Unzicker,W Tel Aviv 1964 (В1/2-В1/2, 84)}) 16... f6
17. Qe2 (17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Nd4 {is by far less effective than in a similar
variation examined in Line 18.} Rfe8 $1 19. Nxe6 Rxe6 {White has serious
problems because he cannot connect rooks due to the hanging b2-pawn.} 20. Rf1
Rae8 $15) (17. Bh6 Nxb2 $5 (17... Rfe8 {is also good.}) 18. Qe2 Rfe8 19. Nd4 (
19. Bxg6 hxg6 20. Qxb2 Bg4 $15 {Kazmierczak,Z (1959)-Haller,P (2041) ICCF
email 2010 (В1/2-В1/2, 33)}) 19... f5 20. Bxf5 Bxf5 21. Qxb2 Be6 $11 {With a
very interesting non-symmetrical position offering both sides chances.}) 17...
Rae8 {Black does not have any problems.} 18. a4 (18. Bh6 Rf7 19. Rad1 Nxe5 20.
Nxe5 fxe5 21. Qxe5 Bc5 22. Rd2 Bd6 23. Qe3 c6 24. Rde2 Rfe7 25. Qd2 Bf5 26.
Rxe7 Rxe7 27. Rxe7 Qxe7 {В1/2-В1/2 Johansen,O (2327)-Andreassen,E (2314) ICCF
email 2007}) 18... Nxe5 19. Nxe5 fxe5 20. Bh6 Rf7 21. Qxe5 Bc5 22. Re2 Rfe7 23.
Qg5 Bf5 24. Rxe7 Qxe7 25. Qxe7 Rxe7 26. Bxf5 gxf5 $11 {Tauber,H (2528)-Walter,
G (2452) ICCF email 2016 (0-1, 29) Most probably White lost on time (yes, it
happens in correspondence chess, too, maybe even more frequently than in
over-the-board chess.)} *

