1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2 {This line has been successfully used by Paul Keres during the '40s,
explaining why it bears his name. White's main idea is to set up pressure on
d5 with Rd1 and then break with c2-c4. Optically, this looks threatening, but
one can also notice that White neglects the queenside development, which
entitles Black to count on equalizing.} Be7 10. Rd1 {Other moves are less
consistent.} (10. c3 Nc5 11. Bc2 d4 {is an improved version of ...d5-d4 in the
9.Nbd2 system.} 12. cxd4 (12. Rd1 $2 Bc4 13. Qe1 d3 14. Na3 Qc8 15. Bb1 Bd5 16.
Qe3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nxe5 $17 {Prange,D-Bach,S Germany 1995 (0-1, 45)}) 12... Nxd4
13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Rd1 Qc4 15. Qxc4 bxc4 $1 $146 {Consolidating control over d3
and opening the b-file for the rooks.} (15... Bxc4 16. Nc3 {leaves the bishop
misplaced on c4.}) 16. Nc3 O-O 17. Be3 Rab8 $11) (10. Nbd2 Nc5 11. c3 Bg4 12.
Rd1 (12. Bc2 d4 13. Be4 Qd7 14. Bxc6 Qxc6 15. cxd4 Ne6 16. h3 Bh5 17. Qe3 O-O {
, with excellent compensation for the pawn due to the control over the light
squares and the bishops' pair.}) 12... Nxb3 13. Nxb3 Qd7 $11 {Black
experiences certain problems with his e5-pawn.}) 10... O-O 11. c4 (11. c3 {
is most actively met with} f5 12. exf6 Bxf6 $11) 11... bxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5 {
Taking advantage of the fact that f2 is not defended.} 13. Be3 {This is forced,
but weakening b2 allows Black to move his queen out of the d-file.} Bxe3 14.
Qxe3 (14. fxe3 $6 {spoils White's structure, allowing Black to leave the pawn
on d5 undefended.} Qe7 15. Bxd5 (15. Rxd5 Rad8 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. Bxe6 Qxe6 $15)
15... Bxd5 16. Rxd5 Rad8 $15 {In both cases Black retrieves the pawn on e5,
maintaining the better structure.}) 14... Qb8 $1 15. Bb3 {Black has a small
lead in development and a free tempo to organize his counterplay.} Qb6 $5 {
Black neutralizes White's queen's pressure on both wings. As we will see in
Line 22, the Isolani on d5 is not weak.} (15... Na5 {is by far more popular,
but Black may face some micro problems after} 16. Nd4) 16. Qe2 (16. Nbd2 Qxe3
17. fxe3 Na5 {Transposes to a variation from the abovementioned 15...Na5 that
is unambitious for White.} 18. Nxe4 Nxb3 19. axb3 dxe4 20. Nd4 c5 21. Nxe6 fxe6
22. Rd6 Rfb8 $11) (16. Qxb6 {is examined in Line 22.}) 16... Ne7 17. Nc3 $1 {
The best way to keep Black's central pawns under control.} (17. Nbd2 Nxd2 18.
Rxd2 c5 $15 {Navarro Alonso,J (2136)-Luis Vitalla, F (2199) Aragon 2008 (В1/
2-В1/2, 22)}) 17... Nxc3 18. bxc3 c5 {Despite its apparent simplicity, this
position requires a certain accuracy from Black. The ideas played in the few
correspondence games available do not have much in common with over-the-board
play.} 19. Ng5 (19. Bc2 h6 20. Nh4 c4 $5 {Delaying f2-f4. If White wishes to
make it possible, he will have to temporarily weaken f2.} ({I hope that you
will excuse me for not recommending the following line:} 20... Rab8 21. f4 g6
22. f5 Bxf5 23. Bxf5 c4+ 24. Kh1 Nxf5 25. Nxf5 gxf5 26. Rxd5 Rfd8 27. Rxd8+
Rxd8 28. Qxc4 {В1/2-В1/2 Atoufi,P-Sutkalenko,D (2275) ICCF email 2016}) 21.
Rab1 (21. Kh1 f6 22. Rab1 Qc7 23. Nf3 Nc6 24. exf6 Rxf6 $11 {Black's pressure
along the f-file and his light space advantage compensate for White's control
of d4.}) 21... Qc5 22. Kh1 Ng6 $1 {Exploiting the vulnerability of the f2-pawn.
} (22... f6 {may still be playable, but optically Black seems a bit under
pressure after} 23. Rb7 Rae8) 23. Nf5 (23. Nxg6 fxg6 24. f3 g5 $11) (23. Nf3
Bg4 $11) 23... Bxf5 24. Bxf5 Rae8 25. e6 Qe7 26. g3 Qf6 27. Rxd5 Nf4 $1 (27...
fxe6 28. Bxg6 Qxg6 29. Rdd1 Rd8 {Should be about equal, but I would prefer
playing without that weakness on e6.}) 28. gxf4 fxe6 $11) 19... c4 $1 {Before
inviting the exchange on e6, Black consolidates his control of the light
squares.} (19... h6 20. Nxe6 Qxe6 (20... fxe6 {runs into} 21. c4 $14) 21. Rd2
c4 22. Bc2 Rab8 23. Rad1 Rb7 24. a4 g6 25. f4 {Jaederholm,B (2410)-Huuskonen,V
(2320) Denmark 1995 (В1/2-В1/2, 31) Once again I am not keen to defend such a
position, even though engines cry out loud that it is dead equal.}) 20. Bc2 h6
21. Nf3 (21. Nxe6 fxe6 $11 {is safe for Black.}) 21... Bg4 22. h3 Bxf3 23. Qxf3
Qb2 {Chances are about equal, but there is a lot of life in this position.
White has to prepare f4-f5 as soon as possible, otherwise his bishop may turn
into a bad piece.} 24. Rdc1 Rad8 (24... Rfe8 $5 25. Qe3 Nc6 26. f4 d4 27. cxd4
(27. Qe4 d3 $11) 27... Nxd4 $11) (24... Qa3 {is my favourite, as it creates
some sort of pin along the third rank.} 25. Qe3 Rab8 26. f4 $6 Rfd8 27. Rab1
Nc6 $15 {, and ...d5-d4 is in the air.}) 25. Qe3 d4 {These are less favourable
circumstances for this pawn break than above, but it should suffice for a draw.
} 26. cxd4 Qxd4 27. Qe4 Qxe4 28. Bxe4 Rd4 29. Bb7 a5 30. Ba6 Ng6 31. Rxc4 Rxc4
32. Bxc4 Nxe5 33. Bb5 Rc8 34. Rd1 Rc5 35. a4 {Kavalek,L (2590)-Smyslov,V (2560)
Solingen 1979 (1-0, 60). The bishop's superiority over the knight is purely
symbolical here, due to the reduced queenside number of pawns.} g5 $1 $11 36.
Rd8+ Kg7 37. Ra8 Rc1+ 38. Kh2 Rc2 $11 {With a possible draw by repetition as}
39. Kg3 {leads nowhere:} (39. f3 Nxf3+ $17) 39... f5 40. f4 Rc3+ 41. Kf2 gxf4
$11 *

