1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. c4 bxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qb8
15. Bb3 Qb6 16. Qxb6 {The most natural move.} cxb6 {White's control over d4
looks inspiring, but his problem is that the reserve knight is undeveloped and
rather far away from that square.} 17. Na3 (17. Nbd2 Nc5 18. Rac1 Rac8 $15 {
White cannot block the central pawn properly.}) (17. Nc3 Nxc3 18. bxc3 {
consolidates control over d4 but offers Black counterplay along the c-file.}
Ne7 19. Nd4 Rac8 $11) (17. Bxd5 $2 {loses material:} Rad8 18. Bb3 Bxb3 $1)
17... Rfd8 18. Nc2 (18. Rac1 Rac8 19. Kf1 (19. Nc2 {Palac,M (2559)-Di Fonzo,V 
(2212) Arvier 2008 (1-0, 36). Black should pursue the same plan as in the
mainline:} Na5) 19... Nc5 20. Nc2 {Panchenko,A-Kharitonov,A Irkutsk 1983 (В1/
2-В1/2, 30)} Nxb3 21. axb3 Bg4 $11) 18... Na5 {The Isolani is generally useful
to sustain outposts. There is a knight on e4 already and the other one hurries
to c4.} 19. Nb4 {This leads to some interesting concrete moments.} (19. Ncd4
Nc4 20. Rab1 Rac8 21. h3 {leads to some sort of static equality. Both players
have placed their pieces optimally but White has to permanently defend b2.
Here are two games that illustrate the possible plans.} g6 (21... h6 22. Re1
Nc5 23. Bc2 Bd7 24. Re2 Re8 25. b3 Na3 26. Rd1 Bb5 27. Re3 Nxc2 28. Nxc2 Nxb3
29. Na3 Rc1 30. Rde1 Rxe1+ 31. Rxe1 Nc5 32. Nxb5 axb5 33. Rb1 Ra8 34. Rxb5 Rxa2
35. Rxb6 Ra1+ $11 {Ivanovic,B (2535)-Timman,J (2630) Belgrade 1987 (В1/2-В1/2,
35)}) 22. Bc2 Bd7 23. Re1 Nc5 24. Re2 a5 25. Kh2 Re8 26. g4 Re7 27. b3 Na3 28.
Rd1 b5 29. Bd3 b4 $11 {The static equality persists, Kovalev,V (2664)-Wagner,D
(2572) Douglas 2018 (В1/2-В1/2, 60)}) 19... Nc4 20. Rab1 (20. Bxc4 dxc4 21.
Nxa6 {is risky adventure, as the knight is far away from any good squares.}
Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 h6 23. Nb4 Ra4 24. a3 c3 25. bxc3 Rxa3 26. h3 Rxc3 27. Rd8+ Kh7
28. Rb8 Bxh3 29. Rxb6 Be6 $15 {White has problems with his pawn on f2,
Tukmakov,V-Kortschnoj,V Moscow 1973 (0-1, 39)}) 20... Nc5 21. Nc6 Re8 22. Nfd4
Rac8 {White's knights are very active but also hanging.} 23. h3 {Preparing
f2-f4.} (23. f4 $6 {is premature:} Bg4 {Suddenly the rooks are vulnerable.} 24.
Rdc1 (24. Re1 $2 Nd3 $19 {wins an exchange.}) 24... Nd2 25. Ra1 Rxc6 26. Nxc6
Ncxb3 27. axb3 Nxb3 $15) 23... Rc7 $1 $146 {Preparing to cut off the knight's
retreat with ...a7-a5.} (23... Bd7 24. Nb4 Rxe5 $2 25. Nf3 Ree8 26. Nxd5 $16 {
Giri,A (2767)-Papp,G (2587) Novi Sad 2016 (В1/2-В1/2, 74)}) (23... a5 {allows}
24. Na7 $14) 24. f4 a5 {Suddenly White is hanging.} 25. Nxe6 (25. f5 Bd7 $19)
25... Nxe6 26. f5 Nc5 27. Bxc4 dxc4 28. Nd4 Nd3 $15 *

