{[%evp 0,22,25,18,25,18,25,15,3,-22,-22,-37,23,17,22,-70,24,-112,26,44,38,41,
41,45,46]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 ({It is useful to compare the lines
examined here with the Berlin Defence:} 3... Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 (5. d4 {
is also relevant for the comparison:} Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+
Kxd8) 5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1) 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1 {Instead of
the strongest and most principled 6.d4, White may be tempted to set up piece
pressure along the e-file. But this works out much less consistently than in
the Berlin Defence, where White can retain some light pressure.} ({Since in
one of the lines below Black exchanges queens after dxe5, it is worth
mentioning} 6. Qe2 {with the same idea:} Nc5 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. d4 Ne6 9. dxe5 {
The same structure as in the line from the comments to move 7 below, but in
this case the black queen faces some space problems. For more details please
refer to the comments to the main line.} Nd4 ({Actually} 9... Bc5 {followed by
. ..Qe7 is also good.}) 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qg4 (11... Bg4 {forces the queen
exchange but practically loses a tempo over the line from the next comment.
Even so, Black's position is preferable:} 12. Rxd4 Bxe2 13. Be3 Bh5 14. Rd2 Rd8
15. c4 {Munoz Pantoja,M (2430)-Petrosyan,T (2441) Barbera del Valles 2015 
(½-½, 104)} Be7 16. Nc3 Rxd2 17. Bxd2 Kd7 $15 {followed by ...Ke6.}) 12. f3 (
12. Qxg4 Bxg4 13. Rd4 Bf5 {leaves Black practically with an extra tempo over
the line above.}) 12... Qf5 (12... Qg6 $17) 13. Nc3 Be6 14. g4 Qg6 15. h4 h5
16. g5 Qf5 $17 {Niechoj,N (1835)-Huebner,W (2083) Bad Ems 2006 (0-1, 26)}) 6...
Nc5 {The same as in the Berlin Defence, Black attacks the bishop. But this
time the bishop does not have the regrouping Bf1 (or Bd3) and will inevitably
be exchanged.} 7. Nc3 {The most intersting try.} (7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. Rxe5+ Be7 9.
Nc3 O-O ({In a blitz game against Hamdouchi, few decades ago, I fell into the
trick} 9... Nxa4 10. Nd5 O-O 11. Nxe7+ Kh8 12. Qh5 {White has a decisive
attack already, but I bulndered the main threat with} d6 13. Qxh7+ $1) 10. d4 (
10. Nd5 $2 Bd6 {wins material.}) 10... Nxa4 11. Nxa4 b5 $17 {Planning ...Bb7.
If} 12. Qf3 Rb8 13. Nc3 Bf6 {the pawn on d4 is hanging.}) (7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. d4
Ne6 9. dxe5 (9. Nxe5 {is better, but after} Bd6 {Back has excellent play due
to his two bishops and free development. The knight on e5 is only apparently
active, as Black can play ...f7-f6 after castling.}) 9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 {
It is useful to compare this position to the main Berlin tabyia above. Black
has the usual control of the light squares and his knight is better placed on
e6 than on f5 (in the Berlin Black many times invests a lot of time to
"correct" the knight's placement). White does not have anything to compensate
for all these, as unlike in the Berlin Defence Black did not lose the right to
castle, meaning that he can connect rooks at leisure.} Bd7 11. Nc3 (11. Ng5
Nxg5 12. Bxg5 Bc5 13. Nc3 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Bg3 O-O-O $15) 11...
Be7 12. Be3 O-O-O 13. Ne4 h6 $15) 7... Be7 (7... Nxa4 {may be playable if
Black remains accurate, but it offers White undeserved active ideas.} 8. Nxe5
Be7 9. Nd5 Nc5 (9... O-O $6 10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. Nxe7+ Kh8 12. Qh5 {is very
active for White.}) 10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. Nxe7 Be6 12. Nf5 O-O $11) 8. Nd5 (8. Bxc6
dxc6 9. Nxe5 Ne6 {is great for Black.}) 8... O-O 9. Bxc6 dxc6 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7
11. d4 Ne6 {½-½ Hamdouchi,H (2567)-Marin,M (2537) Castelldefels 2005 As we
see, Hichem did not get the chance to beat me twice with the same variation.
When we played this game I did not know that he had had this position once
before:} 12. Nxe5 Rd8 13. c3 f6 14. Nd3 Qf7 15. Qb3 a5 16. a4 b6 17. Nf4 {
½-½ Hamdouchi,H (2588) -Delchev,A (2602) Belfort 2004} *

